1
00:00:06,645 --> 00:00:29,379
very good namo tassa

2
00:00:37,914 --> 00:01:00,243
I just want to begin by thanking all those people who have organized this lovely little celebration for me.

3
00:01:01,523 --> 00:01:02,003
Yes.

4
00:01:03,587 --> 00:01:11,459
The organising committee, Aya and Richard and Deya and Mark and Sarah.

5
00:01:12,402 --> 00:01:21,878
And all those people really who've made lovely donations to buy this...

6
00:01:22,921 --> 00:01:30,489
a statue that will go at the back of the pond there, and to fund my little trip to Japan.

7
00:01:30,650 --> 00:01:34,474
And I was relieved to see that I could get a return ticket.

8
00:01:40,280 --> 00:01:51,072
Also, I thank Charles and Heather and Mark and Peter, who've done this very professional recording for us.

9
00:01:52,807 --> 00:01:54,710
And of course, everybody who's chipped in for today.

10
00:01:55,953 --> 00:01:57,856
So we have other birthdays here.

11
00:01:57,936 --> 00:01:59,640
Sarah, her birthday.

12
00:02:00,180 --> 00:02:02,927
And also Andy, who's got the 5-0.

13
00:02:04,308 --> 00:02:07,015
Yes, we're all suffering.

14
00:02:09,118 --> 00:02:12,384
And I think we can bring to mind Stephen Hawking.

15
00:02:12,718 --> 00:02:18,408
We can feel a certain sorrow for David Bowie, didn't quite make his three score and ten.

16
00:02:19,711 --> 00:02:28,044
And we can spend, I think we can all join in with a special regard and good wishes to Kim Jong-un in Korea.

17
00:02:37,323 --> 00:02:43,709
I am delighted that you've taken such joy in my own little birthday.

18
00:02:45,510 --> 00:02:49,014
But of course I myself am depressed.

19
00:02:49,034 --> 00:02:58,704
Yes, well yes, this is the beginning of the steep, the downward trend to decrepitude and senility.

20
00:02:58,723 --> 00:03:05,811
Now there was a card which some thought was telling me that 70 was a new 30.

21
00:03:11,917 --> 00:03:14,199
It's not.

22
00:03:14,218 --> 00:03:15,199
70's serious.

23
00:03:18,584 --> 00:03:18,903
OK.

24
00:03:19,645 --> 00:03:35,822
So, something peculiar's happened to me this year, in the sense that, suddenly, I suppose it's reaching the end of all this building stuff here, too, and feeling very settled outside Sari Panya.

25
00:03:36,823 --> 00:03:39,086
Now, memories of my past life came up.

26
00:03:39,545 --> 00:03:40,287
I mean, this one.

27
00:03:42,798 --> 00:03:44,740
No, this one.

28
00:03:46,461 --> 00:03:47,282
Of my past living.

29
00:03:47,782 --> 00:03:53,068
And I just wondered how it is that I got to this place.

30
00:03:53,569 --> 00:04:01,518
So I thought it was an opportunity, really, to answer the questions that I'm often asked, but I usually palm or palm off with a sentence or two.

31
00:04:01,598 --> 00:04:06,223
It's how I became a Buddhist, how I became a monk, and why do I continue?

32
00:04:08,870 --> 00:04:16,019
So to start at the beginning there, you see, my father was in the RAF.

33
00:04:17,923 --> 00:04:24,872
And they were following the armies up the Tour of Italy when he was billeted on my mother's house.

34
00:04:25,533 --> 00:04:29,560
And they fell in love.

35
00:04:29,579 --> 00:04:33,105
And it seems as though he took AWOL in order to marry her.

36
00:04:33,125 --> 00:04:36,730
And when he got back to Cyprus, they put him in jail for a while.

37
00:04:36,750 --> 00:04:37,711
It's all very romantic.

38
00:04:38,805 --> 00:04:42,910
Anyway, he brought her to Britain and that's when her real depression began.

39
00:04:45,213 --> 00:04:54,362
If you can imagine moving from a hillside village overlooking the Adriatic with the smell of pine in your nostrils and ending up in Manchester.

40
00:04:56,084 --> 00:04:57,165
Black Manchester.

41
00:04:57,264 --> 00:04:59,307
We forget how black the cities were.

42
00:04:59,887 --> 00:05:03,610
Saturated with soot everywhere and pea soup fog.

43
00:05:05,372 --> 00:05:08,255
Anyway, she happily became pregnant with me.

44
00:05:09,704 --> 00:05:11,706
but decided to go home to have me.

45
00:05:12,968 --> 00:05:17,334
And when the time came, they brought in the local midwife.

46
00:05:18,656 --> 00:05:28,487
She was 25, so presumably there was a little difficulty, but either they rushed it or it was her particular way of doing things, but they cut her.

47
00:05:30,591 --> 00:05:36,858
Such was the agony she bit into my uncle's thumb, and he showed me the scar.

48
00:05:38,898 --> 00:05:40,321
Even then I wouldn't come out.

49
00:05:42,425 --> 00:05:45,790
They had to prize me out with forceps.

50
00:05:45,810 --> 00:05:47,012
I mean, what a start.

51
00:05:48,896 --> 00:05:49,718
What a start.

52
00:05:51,903 --> 00:05:56,672
She went on to give birth to two more sons and a daughter.

53
00:05:58,194 --> 00:06:00,939
So I've got two brothers and a lovely sister.

54
00:06:03,096 --> 00:06:04,987
The effect of birth upon us.

55
00:06:06,153 --> 00:06:07,422
Consider the Buddha.

56
00:06:07,442 --> 00:06:10,137
So as soon as he was born, his mother died.

57
00:06:10,740 --> 00:06:16,367
So there must be a feeling there of loss, whether the baby's fully aware of it or not.

58
00:06:16,427 --> 00:06:17,910
There must be a feeling of loss.

59
00:06:18,752 --> 00:06:31,148
And according to certain disciplines like rebirthing, you know, that breathing thing, and Stan Grof, holo, I wasn't gonna say holocaustic, hologramic, whatever it is, breathing.

60
00:06:32,369 --> 00:06:35,333
The birth trauma has a real effect upon us.

61
00:06:35,353 --> 00:06:37,355
You know, it's there within our psyche.

62
00:06:38,702 --> 00:06:48,675
So I know this from the difference between my siblings because my mother said that my sister, who was last 11 years on, fell out.

63
00:06:50,658 --> 00:06:52,321
And she's utterly phlegmatic.

64
00:06:54,603 --> 00:06:55,305
Nothing like me.

65
00:07:00,411 --> 00:07:02,634
So that was my birth.

66
00:07:04,673 --> 00:07:11,088
Now, I want you to imagine this little five-year-old boy being taken to church by his father.

67
00:07:12,502 --> 00:07:13,704
And he's walking into church.

68
00:07:13,725 --> 00:07:15,105
The church is quite big.

69
00:07:15,367 --> 00:07:16,267
It's St. Patrick's.

70
00:07:16,367 --> 00:07:19,050
It belongs to a third generation of Irish.

71
00:07:20,052 --> 00:07:28,122
And as you walk in, your nostrils are suffused with incense, frankincense.

72
00:07:28,142 --> 00:07:29,545
The atmosphere is very warm.

73
00:07:30,605 --> 00:07:31,908
And the people are very quiet.

74
00:07:32,309 --> 00:07:33,310
And then you're sitting there.

75
00:07:33,831 --> 00:07:36,694
And you're taken up into the gallery, into the choir loft.

76
00:07:37,555 --> 00:07:39,658
And your father is conducting.

77
00:07:39,841 --> 00:07:52,959
And at the point where the priest in these wonderful garments comes in with all the altar boys, because it was high mass, you're there as a little boy, a little child, and you're let loose.

78
00:07:52,980 --> 00:08:08,142
You can wander around and you're hanging on to the barrier of the choir overlooking down into the congregation and suddenly Bach or Handel or Sweet Music is coming in.

79
00:08:09,591 --> 00:08:11,555
So this was my introduction into devotion.

80
00:08:12,276 --> 00:08:13,156
I was in ecstasy.

81
00:08:14,720 --> 00:08:18,725
And it's something that I think a lot of children these days don't get.

82
00:08:19,247 --> 00:08:23,031
Not that they don't get it with other things like pop stars and things like that.

83
00:08:24,194 --> 00:08:32,105
But it was my introduction into religion as a real heart-based experience.

84
00:08:33,722 --> 00:08:35,710
And this was to carry on.

85
00:08:36,874 --> 00:08:43,176
So that was, I call, if my first catastrophe was birth, this was my first blessing.

86
00:08:43,561 --> 00:08:54,013
And my mother, being a southern Catholic, they were Roman Catholics, so I should mention that, my mother being a southern European Catholic, it was all about the love of Jesus, you see.

87
00:08:54,493 --> 00:08:56,836
And my father was all Helen Brimstone.

88
00:08:58,837 --> 00:08:59,759
I had a nice balance.

89
00:08:59,778 --> 00:09:01,640
I obviously warmed towards my mother.

90
00:09:02,621 --> 00:09:04,605
Northern Catholicism is very Protestant.

91
00:09:06,527 --> 00:09:07,628
So...

92
00:09:09,429 --> 00:09:17,163
When you convert to a religion, when you actually move into a religion, you move in for various reasons.

93
00:09:17,364 --> 00:09:24,317
Most people who come to Buddhism come because they're suffering, because things have gone wrong and they've heard about meditation and stuff like that.

94
00:09:24,922 --> 00:09:38,179
But to actually begin to develop a heart attachment, a heart, a good attachment, this isn't, not all attachments are evil, a sort of relationship of the heart with your religion is very difficult, because this is done when you're a child.

95
00:09:38,921 --> 00:09:51,638
When you go to Thailand, you'll see little children are brought into the monastery, into the temples, and they bow, and they also have this sandalwood and incense, and they have the chanting.

96
00:09:51,618 --> 00:10:05,528
So that sense of devotion, which is a beautiful emotional state, it's a mental state of praise, of being in a lovely spaced out place, it's absolutely glorious.

97
00:10:05,548 --> 00:10:09,035
And of course you can develop these things into absorptions.

98
00:10:09,774 --> 00:10:13,360
That's very difficult for us because it's a different culture.

99
00:10:13,400 --> 00:10:15,004
We haven't got that sort of background.

100
00:10:15,024 --> 00:10:24,779
So I always think the way into that, the way into a devotional, a sort of heart connection with the Buddhist teaching is through gratitude.

101
00:10:25,840 --> 00:10:32,928
And the more that you consider what the teaching has done for you and for others, etc., etc., then you get this gratitude come up.

102
00:10:33,249 --> 00:10:37,934
And it's very simple to go from gratitude towards love, towards a relationship.

103
00:10:38,436 --> 00:10:40,217
Now, of course, the Buddha is gone.

104
00:10:40,357 --> 00:10:41,700
It's not as though we're relating to the Buddha.

105
00:10:41,740 --> 00:10:44,503
What we're relating to is an image within us of the Buddha.

106
00:10:45,264 --> 00:10:54,294
And in growing that, in a sense, we're actually forming a devotional relationship to the Buddha within us that we want to become.

107
00:10:55,303 --> 00:10:58,988
So it's the Buddha as he appears in daily life.

108
00:10:59,107 --> 00:11:00,509
It's not the transcendent Buddha.

109
00:11:00,909 --> 00:11:03,052
It's the Buddha of compassion, of love, of joy.

110
00:11:03,673 --> 00:11:06,797
And that's why I've got all these statues.

111
00:11:08,599 --> 00:11:11,081
That's the idea of devotion.

112
00:11:12,942 --> 00:11:19,049
I'm trying to squeeze a bit of Dharma out of my autobiography.

113
00:11:20,227 --> 00:11:30,586
So anyway, we moved then to North Manchester, which was all fields at that time, out of Dean G. Mostyn into the lovely fields.

114
00:11:30,905 --> 00:11:32,308
The fields didn't stay fields long.

115
00:11:32,328 --> 00:11:33,230
They were soon built on.

116
00:11:33,730 --> 00:11:37,798
And right at the back of us, they established a cemetery.

117
00:11:39,061 --> 00:11:40,624
So we're at school.

118
00:11:40,683 --> 00:11:43,609
There were over 50 kids in the class.

119
00:11:44,390 --> 00:11:48,197
So 47 was the peak of the baby boom.

120
00:11:48,216 --> 00:11:50,721
It begins in 45 and ends in 65.

121
00:11:51,503 --> 00:11:57,374
And if you look at the graph, it goes zoop on 47 and then begins to slowly come down.

122
00:11:57,394 --> 00:12:00,779
So Theresa May is a boomer.

123
00:12:00,799 --> 00:12:00,899
Okay.

124
00:12:01,623 --> 00:12:05,426
So then, while I was at primary school, a priest turned up.

125
00:12:06,106 --> 00:12:11,471
And he gave us this wonderful talk with pictures about the missions.

126
00:12:12,972 --> 00:12:16,476
He showed us pictures of Flores, which is a beautiful island in Indonesia.

127
00:12:16,937 --> 00:12:18,518
He showed us pictures about New Guinea.

128
00:12:18,979 --> 00:12:20,821
And he showed us pictures about South America.

129
00:12:20,880 --> 00:12:24,783
And he talked about the wonderful things that priests did out there, missionaries.

130
00:12:25,365 --> 00:12:31,090
And if anybody felt like they might be drawn to that sort of thing, then they should get in contact.

131
00:12:32,351 --> 00:12:41,642
So anyway, I got the 11 plus and I went to Zaverian College, which was a grammar school.

132
00:12:41,942 --> 00:12:46,287
But two of my friends from that school went to St. Richard's College.

133
00:12:47,006 --> 00:12:51,672
And during that year, for some reason, it came to me that that's what I wanted to do.

134
00:12:52,653 --> 00:13:00,942
My mother was fiercely against it, but my father was like that, but it was my Aunt Rose who really wanted a priest in the family.

135
00:13:02,827 --> 00:13:06,893
Come the age of 12, I'm off on the train down to St. Richard's College.

136
00:13:08,014 --> 00:13:17,025
And for me, it was entering into two years of undiluted heaven, because it was all about doing exactly what you want to do.

137
00:13:17,326 --> 00:13:18,948
And that's when you're most happiest, isn't it?

138
00:13:19,448 --> 00:13:25,836
When you're doing exactly what you want to do in an unpressured situation, you're in perfect joy.

139
00:13:26,337 --> 00:13:27,198
Correct?

140
00:13:27,178 --> 00:13:30,783
For instance, a hobby, right?

141
00:13:30,802 --> 00:13:35,067
So the routine there was up about half past six, seven o'clock.

142
00:13:35,788 --> 00:13:36,948
We went down for mass.

143
00:13:37,370 --> 00:13:43,056
After mass, we went out in most weathers, only in the most severe, to do the old army exercise.

144
00:13:45,918 --> 00:13:49,042
Back in, into breakfast, clean up.

145
00:13:49,062 --> 00:13:53,506
School starts nine o'clock, all the way through to five o'clock.

146
00:13:53,486 --> 00:13:59,474
And all that time, apart from a little break at lunch, I remember it was in silence.

147
00:13:59,494 --> 00:14:01,616
Can you imagine that for a 12-year-old these days?

148
00:14:03,057 --> 00:14:10,106
At 6 o'clock, we went in to study, and at 8 o'clock, we were finally let free and we could play games down in the big game room.

149
00:14:12,188 --> 00:14:15,613
Imagine a 12-year-old day like today.

150
00:14:18,208 --> 00:14:32,028
So, and I really got into it, I mean it was, all I remember is just being blissed out and hating going home, you know, and having to come back because it was just there that I found my joy.

151
00:14:32,089 --> 00:14:40,520
Then, something began to happen which promised a different sort

152
00:14:40,702 --> 00:14:41,604
of joy.

153
00:14:42,384 --> 00:14:47,230
It promised gold, but it turned into glitter.

154
00:14:47,951 --> 00:14:51,496
And the joy it promised finally ended up with frustration.

155
00:14:52,717 --> 00:14:53,219
Puberty.

156
00:14:57,303 --> 00:14:59,927
Even Mick Jagger could get no satisfaction.

157
00:15:01,549 --> 00:15:02,490
And he tried.

158
00:15:03,032 --> 00:15:10,221
Anyway, we were let out every so often to go for a walk on a Sunday.

159
00:15:11,197 --> 00:15:14,208
And there were about six of us, five of us on the trip.

160
00:15:14,229 --> 00:15:17,982
And as we got down, we suddenly had this idea that we'd smoke.

161
00:15:18,706 --> 00:15:21,470
Now, teenagers are by nature rebellious.

162
00:15:22,071 --> 00:15:23,854
The order didn't smoke.

163
00:15:23,874 --> 00:15:27,038
And it was a German order begun by a German priest.

164
00:15:27,860 --> 00:15:29,702
And it was mainly German and American.

165
00:15:30,464 --> 00:15:35,552
And the joke was, we don't smoke, so we drink.

166
00:15:35,572 --> 00:15:40,980
S-V-D. And so it was a sort of little rebellion to go and get some cigarettes.

167
00:15:41,380 --> 00:15:44,004
And we decided to steal them.

168
00:15:47,038 --> 00:15:53,691
There was an old lady who ran a shop at this bridge on the Worcester Canal.

169
00:15:54,511 --> 00:16:00,162
And as we entered in, we'd had it all figured out, somebody distracted her and somebody took the cigarettes.

170
00:16:01,565 --> 00:16:04,870
And I can't remember what my job was.

171
00:16:04,890 --> 00:16:05,532
And I daren't.

172
00:16:08,616 --> 00:16:09,238
So I'll leave that.

173
00:16:09,298 --> 00:16:11,982
I'll leave that.

174
00:16:12,789 --> 00:16:13,910
Well, we smoked, of course.

175
00:16:14,572 --> 00:16:23,181
And when we got back in the evening after lunch, we were all called to the prefect's office, one headmaster prefect.

176
00:16:24,383 --> 00:16:30,028
And he told us that, he asked us, had we taken cigarettes from this lady?

177
00:16:31,149 --> 00:16:31,951
And we all said yes.

178
00:16:34,413 --> 00:16:35,215
She was no fool, eh?

179
00:16:35,674 --> 00:16:38,097
We were probably the only customers the whole day.

180
00:16:39,359 --> 00:16:42,763
There was nobody, that in the middle of nowhere.

181
00:16:44,717 --> 00:16:48,962
So we were dismissed, and we thought, well, that's it, you know.

182
00:16:49,804 --> 00:16:53,428
There was no corporal punishment in the seminary at all.

183
00:16:53,609 --> 00:16:55,711
If I was at Zaverian, you'd have been beaten.

184
00:16:55,751 --> 00:17:05,365
Anyway, about a day or so later, we were all called for a talk in the main, in this big classroom.

185
00:17:05,384 --> 00:17:09,509
And the rector, who was in charge of the whole place,

186
00:17:10,267 --> 00:17:14,010
announced that certain boys had stolen.

187
00:17:14,751 --> 00:17:18,516
And he called our names and he said, you are expelled.

188
00:17:21,318 --> 00:17:23,580
Can you imagine that?

189
00:17:23,800 --> 00:17:26,943
I was three months off my GCEs and they kicked me out.

190
00:17:31,088 --> 00:17:35,933
Anyway, I got back and because of that, my GCEs went all over the place.

191
00:17:36,054 --> 00:17:37,454
I had about four GCEs.

192
00:17:37,474 --> 00:17:38,957
I had to take my English again.

193
00:17:40,102 --> 00:17:48,529
And unfortunately, because the education was mainly by Americans, who I don't think really understood the English GCE system at the time.

194
00:17:49,250 --> 00:17:53,815
So what happened was, I ended up with subjects that I had virtually no interest in.

195
00:17:54,214 --> 00:17:56,217
Latin, French, and history.

196
00:17:56,597 --> 00:17:59,420
I had a bit of interest in history.

197
00:18:00,040 --> 00:18:01,801
And so life went on.

198
00:18:02,482 --> 00:18:05,205
And I didn't do well at the GCEs.

199
00:18:06,026 --> 00:18:08,808
And I remember talking to my father.

200
00:18:08,788 --> 00:18:09,970
about this.

201
00:18:10,330 --> 00:18:22,505
Now, when they expelled, when I was thrown out, that was a cut off of a vocation.

202
00:18:23,105 --> 00:18:31,275
This vocation to be a priest remained in me as a really strong, tremendous urge for three years till I was over 19.

203
00:18:32,817 --> 00:18:34,137
Why couldn't I go back?

204
00:18:35,147 --> 00:18:36,690
Why couldn't I go back?

205
00:18:36,710 --> 00:18:39,011
It's because they never forgave me.

206
00:18:40,133 --> 00:18:43,395
I can't tell you how important it is to forgive your enemies.

207
00:18:44,176 --> 00:18:50,423
What happened was, come the GCE, I turned up and they gave me a room in an outer building.

208
00:18:51,483 --> 00:18:55,407
I had to go into the exam room at a different entrance from everybody else.

209
00:18:56,189 --> 00:19:00,252
I wasn't allowed to talk to anybody and they weren't allowed to talk to me.

210
00:19:00,393 --> 00:19:03,957
In other words, I was excommunicated.

211
00:19:04,155 --> 00:19:06,740
And there was no way you can come back on that.

212
00:19:07,381 --> 00:19:14,392
If a priest or somebody come up and said, look, give it a couple of years and then, you know, you can join another order.

213
00:19:14,813 --> 00:19:17,396
I'd have had an in, but I had this block.

214
00:19:17,477 --> 00:19:18,157
I couldn't move.

215
00:19:19,500 --> 00:19:28,054
So if you have any pity on your enemies, on all of them, do forgive them because it allows them to forgive themselves.

216
00:19:29,484 --> 00:19:38,701
And of course, in our offering forgiveness, we empty our own hearts of the revenge and the hurt and all that sort of stuff.

217
00:19:39,256 --> 00:19:45,967
Now, it doesn't mean to say that you've got to have somebody's forgiveness in order to forgive yourself, but it just makes it much easier.

218
00:19:47,869 --> 00:19:56,383
So I went on then to about 19, and my father pointed out to me that since I was lost, I had no clue what to do with my life at this point.

219
00:19:56,864 --> 00:19:58,226
I'm completely lost.

220
00:19:58,246 --> 00:19:59,127
He said, why don't you teach?

221
00:19:59,288 --> 00:20:01,872
He said, you can travel with teaching.

222
00:20:01,852 --> 00:20:04,516
They must have known I was, you know, unsettled.

223
00:20:05,116 --> 00:20:12,929
So I decided, I didn't go into university, so I went down to St. Mary's College, which was then a Catholic training college.

224
00:20:13,329 --> 00:20:14,932
It's now a university.

225
00:20:16,094 --> 00:20:18,156
And it was the year they were introducing the B.Ed.

226
00:20:18,837 --> 00:20:25,147
And instead of doing the B.Ed., I did the other offering, which was a degree course and a teacher training course.

227
00:20:25,167 --> 00:20:29,934
And it was during this time that I completely forgot about being a priest.

228
00:20:31,061 --> 00:20:35,509
I finally began to enjoy a bit of life.

229
00:20:35,528 --> 00:20:39,034
But there's this underlying meaninglessness.

230
00:20:39,134 --> 00:20:45,703
There's this underlying boredom that comes because nothing you're doing is of any direct meaning to your own heart.

231
00:20:46,384 --> 00:20:49,108
And so what you overlay it with is distraction.

232
00:20:49,690 --> 00:20:55,698
You know, you get drunk, you chase women, you do all sorts of daft things.

233
00:20:55,878 --> 00:20:58,082
And that went on for a little while until...

234
00:21:00,846 --> 00:21:04,231
And it was during that time I fell in love.

235
00:21:04,251 --> 00:21:04,932
Oh my goodness.

236
00:21:04,972 --> 00:21:07,176
Well, you know what the first time is, you see.

237
00:21:07,196 --> 00:21:09,941
So I'm completely sozzled, right?

238
00:21:09,961 --> 00:21:16,230
And on one steamy, love-drenched night, she fell pregnant.

239
00:21:17,612 --> 00:21:23,181
This was my third catastrophe.

240
00:21:23,201 --> 00:21:27,968
So now in a Catholic community, for that to happen is a horror story.

241
00:21:28,386 --> 00:21:32,159
The abortion law had just been introduced, so it was legal.

242
00:21:33,502 --> 00:21:40,506
Let's not confuse legal with moral, just because in a liberal society, many of our personal decisions are left to us.

243
00:21:41,818 --> 00:21:44,343
But I just couldn't go there.

244
00:21:44,442 --> 00:21:49,270
It just wasn't on my to-do list, getting married and having children.

245
00:21:50,152 --> 00:21:51,554
So we struggled with it.

246
00:21:51,574 --> 00:21:52,454
We both struggled with it.

247
00:21:52,496 --> 00:21:54,459
She would have been, I think, happy going that way.

248
00:21:55,240 --> 00:21:57,663
And eventually I had to be true to my own heart.

249
00:21:58,003 --> 00:22:03,152
And I went up to visit the parents and I said, look, I can't marry you.

250
00:22:03,570 --> 00:22:06,094
I'll support them.

251
00:22:06,114 --> 00:22:11,359
It was a sort of way of getting myself into that position where eventually I'd sort of marry.

252
00:22:11,380 --> 00:22:19,308
It was a sort of an in-between place, which I felt sort of happy with, that I wasn't entrapped, and then finally I'd probably give in.

253
00:22:19,929 --> 00:22:24,855
But to the family, it just wasn't a no-go, and they just saw disaster for her daughter.

254
00:22:26,616 --> 00:22:31,182
They had connections with surgeons and stuff, and so she had an abortion.

255
00:22:32,730 --> 00:22:40,598
I never felt really bad personally about that because I was never brought into that decision making.

256
00:22:41,420 --> 00:22:43,902
And of course I'm part of that whole process.

257
00:22:45,144 --> 00:23:00,138
But if you go on the website and just type in something like reactions to abortion, you'll see pages after pages of men and women who really regret, no matter what good reason they had, actually regret that whole process.

258
00:23:00,118 --> 00:23:13,714
So it's there, shall we say, within my psyche, that at some part of my life there was an abuse of my sexual powers, even though it was a very wonderful moment.

259
00:23:15,576 --> 00:23:18,180
Buddhism is no different from other religions.

260
00:23:18,359 --> 00:23:20,563
As soon as there's conception, there's consciousness.

261
00:23:21,202 --> 00:23:22,444
So there's a living being.

262
00:23:22,664 --> 00:23:24,146
There's no way out of that.

263
00:23:26,509 --> 00:23:27,830
That's what's understood, anyway.

264
00:23:28,807 --> 00:23:34,258
And this further, I think what this did to me was it further alienated me.

265
00:23:34,278 --> 00:23:37,104
It further alienated me from my own heart.

266
00:23:37,625 --> 00:23:45,059
It further put me into a position of what you might call an underlying despair, which I never really looked at.

267
00:23:45,200 --> 00:23:46,983
It was just there underneath it.

268
00:23:46,963 --> 00:24:02,931
the boredom, the meaninglessness, and then this tragedy and all that just lay down upon me as a sort of despair, which every occasion would actually lend me in a sort of angry depression.

269
00:24:03,892 --> 00:24:05,976
But it never lasted long because I'm very sanguine.

270
00:24:07,939 --> 00:24:09,141
And then one day...

271
00:24:10,623 --> 00:24:15,490
I was 21, 1968, 1968, very important date, 1968.

272
00:24:15,529 --> 00:24:21,278
That was the student revolutions, if you remember, in Paris and all that.

273
00:24:21,298 --> 00:24:28,287
And I lay in bed on a Sunday and I said to myself, I wonder what will happen if I don't go to church.

274
00:24:29,169 --> 00:24:34,316
Now in those days, if you didn't go to church, it was a mortal sin.

275
00:24:35,457 --> 00:24:38,942
And if you didn't get to confess to a priest

276
00:24:39,192 --> 00:24:41,675
and you died, you went to hell forever.

277
00:24:42,517 --> 00:24:43,478
I mean, that was the teaching.

278
00:24:43,939 --> 00:24:45,381
So it was a big decision.

279
00:24:45,942 --> 00:24:49,266
They changed all that in the mid-60s with Pope John XXIII.

280
00:24:50,327 --> 00:24:55,174
And I said to myself, if I don't go to church today, let's see what happens.

281
00:24:56,395 --> 00:24:57,057
Nothing happened.

282
00:24:57,577 --> 00:24:58,298
So I never went again.

283
00:25:01,383 --> 00:25:06,009
I know, it's the most ridiculous thing to do.

284
00:25:07,406 --> 00:25:13,355
And what it manifests really was that the religion had now lost that connection of devotion.

285
00:25:13,415 --> 00:25:14,978
It had just become an empty ritual.

286
00:25:15,117 --> 00:25:19,304
I was just turning up for the mass, receiving communion, et cetera, et cetera.

287
00:25:19,324 --> 00:25:20,946
And it had lost its potency.

288
00:25:20,967 --> 00:25:26,114
And I think also there might have been guilt about the abortion and all that sort of stuff.

289
00:25:26,453 --> 00:25:28,217
And so there was a cutoff there.

290
00:25:28,196 --> 00:25:31,300
Now, what this did, of course, was it deepened my alienation.

291
00:25:31,682 --> 00:25:34,204
It deepened my alienation to the whole thing.

292
00:25:34,605 --> 00:25:37,388
In other words, I found myself where Nietzsche found himself.

293
00:25:37,409 --> 00:25:42,675
I only discovered Nietzsche fairly recently because God is dead.

294
00:25:43,096 --> 00:25:46,981
We've killed him.

295
00:25:47,484 --> 00:25:48,586
Nietzsche struggled with that.

296
00:25:48,686 --> 00:25:59,500
I mean, you know, he came up with the answer of a sort of the courage to face the sufferings and the death of life and to sort of somehow rise above it.

297
00:25:59,921 --> 00:26:06,809
And that's what he meant by the superman or supraman, the ubermensch.

298
00:26:11,498 --> 00:26:16,464
The Buddha himself, if you remember, had that sort of existential crisis.

299
00:26:16,605 --> 00:26:18,827
I mean, he puts it in the myth.

300
00:26:18,847 --> 00:26:27,921
There's a myth surrounding seeing a sick person, an aging person, and a corpse, and this person sitting under a tree.

301
00:26:28,803 --> 00:26:37,454
And the whole thing is about him in his young 20s coming to realize that actually what he's heading towards is sickness, aging, and death.

302
00:26:37,434 --> 00:26:45,284
and that this image of the Samana, of the recluse sitting under a tree, suggested some sort of an escape.

303
00:26:45,904 --> 00:26:50,670
So we have to, I think, imagine the Buddha that he himself is going through an existential crisis.

304
00:26:51,330 --> 00:26:55,895
And it's so strong within him to find the answer to this that he leaves his family.

305
00:26:56,257 --> 00:27:00,642
In his case, his just-born child.

306
00:27:00,622 --> 00:27:06,375
So I think from our point of view, this is where the Buddha's at.

307
00:27:07,499 --> 00:27:10,205
The meaningfulness of life is gone.

308
00:27:10,405 --> 00:27:12,791
It's an existential angst.

309
00:27:14,492 --> 00:27:16,977
And that's where I was, really, with this existential anxiety.

310
00:27:16,997 --> 00:27:19,540
Now, I don't want to give you the impression that I was going around moping and all that.

311
00:27:19,560 --> 00:27:21,344
No, I was still getting drunk and having a good time.

312
00:27:21,724 --> 00:27:33,884
It's just that every so often in silent moments, just by yourself, you suddenly sink into this area of just sheer boredom, a sort of a despair about life.

313
00:27:33,903 --> 00:27:35,326
You're just living it.

314
00:27:36,208 --> 00:27:38,711
And then came my third blessing.

315
00:27:39,130 --> 00:27:42,576
We went to see Waiting for Godot by Beckett.

316
00:27:42,657 --> 00:27:46,926
Now some of you probably don't know that play because it's years old now.

317
00:27:46,946 --> 00:27:52,699
But it's basically about two tramps who are having these gorgeous conversations waiting for Godot.

318
00:27:52,880 --> 00:27:54,663
Godot's going to come and sort it all out.

319
00:27:55,605 --> 00:27:58,471
And the same thing happens in the second act.

320
00:27:58,451 --> 00:28:02,559
And in the first act, two people come, walk across the stage.

321
00:28:02,861 --> 00:28:03,863
Don't go into too detail.

322
00:28:04,042 --> 00:28:06,949
But in the second act, one's gone blind and the other one's gone dumb.

323
00:28:07,691 --> 00:28:09,555
And in the first act, there are leaves on the tree.

324
00:28:09,714 --> 00:28:11,598
In the second act, there's no leaves.

325
00:28:11,618 --> 00:28:15,988
So here are the two tramps waiting for Godot, and everything's just getting worse.

326
00:28:17,048 --> 00:28:24,564
I came out of that play, even though it was just an amateur production by a college, absolutely enthused.

327
00:28:24,604 --> 00:28:25,586
I couldn't stop talking about it.

328
00:28:25,605 --> 00:28:26,567
They all thought I'd gone mad.

329
00:28:27,711 --> 00:28:35,547
But to me, it just caught this whole existential problem of what is the point if in the end you just die?

330
00:28:37,180 --> 00:28:43,787
And I thought at this point, just to get across this, I'd read out a poem by Beckett, which I came across much later.

331
00:28:44,847 --> 00:28:55,499
I spent a lot of time writing about nothingness, well, doggerel anyway, and what it meant to just come to the end, to just finish, to just, and that's it, you're gone, is it?

332
00:28:56,420 --> 00:29:01,385
So let me just read this little poem to you, see what you think.

333
00:29:01,405 --> 00:29:06,411
Just think, if all this, one day,

334
00:29:08,112 --> 00:29:22,384
all this one day, one fine day, just think, if one day, one fine day, all this stopped.

335
00:29:24,406 --> 00:29:24,666
Get it?

336
00:29:30,412 --> 00:29:36,938
So that was the underlying existential problem, right, that I was sort of battling with.

337
00:29:37,626 --> 00:29:49,238
In terms of my emotional life, when I wasn't sort of being extrovert and going out there, there was this, there's a lovely poem by Gerald Manley Hopkins, that gets it across.

338
00:29:49,798 --> 00:29:52,760
And I carried this now for a long time.

339
00:29:53,500 --> 00:29:58,286
But it gives you an idea of, I think it's just a wonderful piece of poetry.

340
00:30:02,970 --> 00:30:07,413
I wake and feel the fell of dark, not day.

341
00:30:09,367 --> 00:30:13,813
What hours, what black hours We have spent this night!

342
00:30:14,775 --> 00:30:22,203
What sights, heart, you saw, Ways you went, and more must In longer lights delay!

343
00:30:23,605 --> 00:30:29,893
With witness I speak this, But where I say hours, I mean years, I mean life.

344
00:30:31,555 --> 00:30:38,143
My lament is cries countless, Cries like dead letters Sent to dearest hymn,

345
00:30:38,696 --> 00:30:40,660
that lives, alas, away.

346
00:30:42,542 --> 00:30:44,766
I am gall, I am heartburn.

347
00:30:45,807 --> 00:30:47,730
God's most deep decree.

348
00:30:48,672 --> 00:30:50,273
Bitter would have me taste.

349
00:30:51,896 --> 00:30:53,499
My taste was me.

350
00:30:55,000 --> 00:31:01,211
Bones built in me, flesh filled, blood brimmed the curse.

351
00:31:01,230 --> 00:31:06,038
Self-yeast of spirit, a dull dough sours.

352
00:31:07,654 --> 00:31:13,346
I see the lost are like this, and they're scourged to be as I am mine.

353
00:31:14,469 --> 00:31:17,476
They're sweating cells, but worse.

354
00:31:19,440 --> 00:31:19,579
Ooh.

355
00:31:20,221 --> 00:31:22,707
Isn't that good, eh?

356
00:31:22,987 --> 00:31:24,230
They're sweating cells.

357
00:31:25,031 --> 00:31:25,613
I love it.

358
00:31:29,440 --> 00:31:37,167
So then, actually, I've gone and forgotten my little, my centerpiece.

359
00:31:37,228 --> 00:31:37,969
I'm so sorry.

360
00:31:38,288 --> 00:31:39,691
I'll have to go back to my birth.

361
00:31:40,250 --> 00:31:40,731
Do you mind?

362
00:31:41,553 --> 00:31:48,239
I'm sorry, I don't know what's wrong with me.

363
00:31:48,259 --> 00:31:52,564
After that terrible birth, we seem to have both recovered.

364
00:31:56,087 --> 00:31:56,528
Eh?

365
00:31:58,616 --> 00:32:00,280
I hadn't seen this picture for years.

366
00:32:00,362 --> 00:32:03,851
And when I saw it, I thought, well, blow me down.

367
00:32:03,871 --> 00:32:06,637
And two things came to mind when I saw it.

368
00:32:06,657 --> 00:32:12,113
I thought, first of all, we remember our mothers as old, in old age.

369
00:32:12,212 --> 00:32:15,141
We forget they were all lovely young women.

370
00:32:15,863 --> 00:32:23,253
And the other thing was that little child, if it was just shown to me, there's no way I'd make a connection with that child at all.

371
00:32:24,295 --> 00:32:25,678
I mean, this is the 10th body.

372
00:32:26,499 --> 00:32:31,926
Hmm, maybe.

373
00:32:31,946 --> 00:32:33,229
Well, no, he's got hair.

374
00:32:33,950 --> 00:32:34,230
He's got hair.

375
00:32:34,349 --> 00:32:35,010
He's got hair.

376
00:32:37,714 --> 00:32:38,977
There's no way I'd make a connection.

377
00:32:38,997 --> 00:32:41,820
This is my 10th body, if we're to believe biology.

378
00:32:42,281 --> 00:32:45,567
Every 10 years, you completely change all the atoms in your body.

379
00:32:47,098 --> 00:32:51,461
Anyway, sorry about that.

380
00:32:51,481 --> 00:32:52,266
I'm going to leave you here.

381
00:32:52,634 --> 00:33:00,103
So okay, so I get, I leave, the relationship breaks up.

382
00:33:00,222 --> 00:33:02,965
I can't handle it anymore.

383
00:33:04,067 --> 00:33:10,795
So anyway, I'm in Spain and I'm looking for my friends and I've lost them.

384
00:33:11,394 --> 00:33:12,916
I've arrived there sometime later.

385
00:33:13,538 --> 00:33:17,702
And I pick up a telegram from the local post office.

386
00:33:17,722 --> 00:33:18,844
Do you remember telegrams?

387
00:33:19,262 --> 00:33:20,286
Yeah, fantastic.

388
00:33:21,008 --> 00:33:22,132
You get it out through the telegram.

389
00:33:22,271 --> 00:33:26,925
And it said, congratulations, son, BA and teaching certificate.

390
00:33:26,945 --> 00:33:29,212
And I went up onto a high rock and overlooked the sea.

391
00:33:29,232 --> 00:33:31,720
And I said to myself, there's no way in this world I want to teach.

392
00:33:34,315 --> 00:33:38,098
So I went down and camped in this camp.

393
00:33:38,118 --> 00:33:40,221
And that night, there was a torrential rain.

394
00:33:40,241 --> 00:33:50,011
I woke up with the tent around me, completely sodden with sand and everything, staggered to the drink area, the, what do you call it?

395
00:33:50,393 --> 00:33:52,015
It's where people drink and stuff like that.

396
00:33:52,935 --> 00:33:55,439
And looking pretty miserable for myself.

397
00:33:55,659 --> 00:33:58,602
And I met this bloke called Dave.

398
00:33:59,307 --> 00:34:00,489
And we began talking.

399
00:34:01,069 --> 00:34:04,535
And by the end of the evening, we decided to travel together across the world.

400
00:34:05,457 --> 00:34:05,998
Simple as that.

401
00:34:06,519 --> 00:34:06,739
See?

402
00:34:07,220 --> 00:34:15,432
So I came back, and I got a job through somebody I knew as a rep for selling audiovisuals to schools.

403
00:34:16,094 --> 00:34:18,577
And there was lots of money in education, so I made lots of money.

404
00:34:19,018 --> 00:34:24,387
And I was traveling all over Cornwall and all over Wales selling this stuff to schools.

405
00:34:24,367 --> 00:34:28,284
And I gathered something like a thousand pounds, which must be what?

406
00:34:28,385 --> 00:34:29,570
It's a lot of money these days, isn't it?

407
00:34:29,590 --> 00:34:30,494
A thousand pounds.

408
00:34:31,740 --> 00:34:33,702
And come the year, off we went.

409
00:34:34,684 --> 00:34:44,152
And during that time, remember, all this time I've got this thing going on, this nothingness and this stuff in the heart.

410
00:34:44,192 --> 00:34:54,780
But because of the joy of travel, just the constant new information coming in and the libel of it, it was all sort of underneath.

411
00:34:54,860 --> 00:34:57,123
It would only come up in the gloomier moments.

412
00:34:58,523 --> 00:35:01,427
So anyway, we went off and we started...

413
00:35:02,268 --> 00:35:03,690
off towards North Africa.

414
00:35:03,731 --> 00:35:08,059
We went down to, saw all the stuff in Egypt, the usual stuff, you know, ride a camel and all that.

415
00:35:08,559 --> 00:35:15,773
Went over to Khartoum, lay on the luggage rack to sleep and woke up with sand everywhere because of a sandstorm.

416
00:35:16,514 --> 00:35:20,001
Got onto a boat down to Juba, which is now the capital of South Sudan.

417
00:35:20,581 --> 00:35:25,170
And for 10 days, we were looking at the amazing site of reeds.

418
00:35:26,449 --> 00:35:28,954
The reeds were so tall, they went up above the boat.

419
00:35:29,315 --> 00:35:32,681
And the boat just plowed through this canal, which was the Nile.

420
00:35:32,981 --> 00:35:35,585
And all you saw for 10 days was reeds.

421
00:35:35,606 --> 00:35:37,789
And because we didn't have much money, we were just eating bread.

422
00:35:38,931 --> 00:35:40,355
So this was a really gloomy time.

423
00:35:40,574 --> 00:35:45,083
And that's when I wrote most of my doggerel about nothingness.

424
00:35:46,260 --> 00:35:46,742
Yeah.

425
00:35:48,125 --> 00:35:50,329
Got down to Juba.

426
00:35:50,429 --> 00:35:51,672
We flew across to Entebbe.

427
00:35:51,692 --> 00:35:54,637
We made this amazing bus ride across Africa.

428
00:35:55,539 --> 00:35:57,021
I slept on the back seat.

429
00:35:57,101 --> 00:35:59,786
And every so often, I was in midair as he ran over an elephant.

430
00:35:59,806 --> 00:36:01,670
It was just unbelievable.

431
00:36:01,650 --> 00:36:06,601
Got to Mombasa, stayed with his brother, but we didn't get on so well.

432
00:36:06,641 --> 00:36:09,347
So we went up the beach and camped up there.

433
00:36:09,807 --> 00:36:12,673
And there we got stolen.

434
00:36:12,894 --> 00:36:22,173
All our traveling checks were stolen, which was fantastic because when you got to India, you got on the black market and made a lot of money.

435
00:36:22,576 --> 00:36:23,177
Terrible, isn't it?

436
00:36:23,858 --> 00:36:25,380
And they stole my father's watch.

437
00:36:25,860 --> 00:36:32,291
He'd given me this gold watch that he had been given after he'd finished his time as a headmaster at St. Patrick's.

438
00:36:32,851 --> 00:36:37,398
And it had inscribed on it at the back, and it was a precious thing, you know?

439
00:36:37,739 --> 00:36:44,469
So I wrote him a letter expressing my sense of sorrow and my love of him and all that, you see.

440
00:36:44,769 --> 00:36:49,797
Well, when his reply came back, you know, about three or four months later...

441
00:36:49,777 --> 00:36:51,661
He said, thank you, son.

442
00:36:51,681 --> 00:36:52,501
Bit sentimental.

443
00:36:52,521 --> 00:37:01,253
So we get to India.

444
00:37:01,273 --> 00:37:08,824
So we get this cattle boat across the Indian Sea from Mombasa to Bombay, playing chess all the time.

445
00:37:09,244 --> 00:37:10,365
Lots of travelers, by the way.

446
00:37:10,567 --> 00:37:12,028
There wasn't many going down Egypt.

447
00:37:12,048 --> 00:37:14,711
But by the time we got to Africa, the boat was full of Westerners.

448
00:37:14,733 --> 00:37:15,353
It was all hippies.

449
00:37:16,875 --> 00:37:17,996
I was dressed in purple.

450
00:37:18,989 --> 00:37:22,454
So we take this boat all the way across to Bombay, and we do the usual trip.

451
00:37:22,474 --> 00:37:25,418
And we finally end up in Nepal.

452
00:37:25,898 --> 00:37:27,240
And that's when we got really stoned.

453
00:37:27,981 --> 00:37:31,887
Up in Nepal, lots of these stones full of dope.

454
00:37:33,971 --> 00:37:39,157
And there were these lovely hippie sort of gatherings where we'd all sit in a circle with a chillum.

455
00:37:43,576 --> 00:37:45,699
That's ridiculous, isn't it?

456
00:37:45,760 --> 00:37:47,684
And that lasted for a while.

457
00:37:48,465 --> 00:37:51,670
And then we made our way down to Calcutta.

458
00:37:51,871 --> 00:37:53,134
And Calcutta was at war.

459
00:37:53,193 --> 00:37:56,320
That was the Indo-Pakistan war where Bangladesh split off.

460
00:37:56,900 --> 00:37:58,423
And so there was no planes going out.

461
00:37:58,443 --> 00:37:59,847
So we were stuck there for two weeks.

462
00:38:01,108 --> 00:38:08,576
And what I did every day, so this was one of my big awakenings.

463
00:38:08,596 --> 00:38:11,039
When you went to India, this time it wasn't so bad.

464
00:38:11,099 --> 00:38:17,425
But in those days, sickness, destitution was in your face.

465
00:38:17,525 --> 00:38:18,907
It was in your face.

466
00:38:18,927 --> 00:38:24,851
And in Calcutta, they have a huge park with this massive statue of Queen Victoria, which I presume they got rid of now.

467
00:38:25,413 --> 00:38:28,416
And there was a massive road, a circuit road going around.

468
00:38:28,396 --> 00:38:31,961
That road was packed tight with the sick.

469
00:38:32,402 --> 00:38:35,547
Elephantitis, everything, apart from lepers, all the way around.

470
00:38:35,668 --> 00:38:36,990
And they were lying on the pavement.

471
00:38:37,150 --> 00:38:40,817
And when you saw that, you understood Mother Teresa's compassion.

472
00:38:41,458 --> 00:38:43,320
Because many of them would have died just there.

473
00:38:44,483 --> 00:38:47,248
So anyway, I saw that.

474
00:38:48,358 --> 00:38:51,663
That sort of thing I'm not used to, I'm not ready to receive.

475
00:38:51,702 --> 00:38:55,286
I'm aware of the suffering, but I'm not ready to receive it.

476
00:38:55,306 --> 00:39:02,215
Every day I went to this Sikh restaurant to get curry, and I would always ask for a glass of water.

477
00:39:02,356 --> 00:39:08,061
And when they brought the glass of water, which was a pint glass, you'd always leave a nice oily thumbprint on the side.

478
00:39:08,583 --> 00:39:12,947
I don't know how it was that I was in India for so long and never caught anything.

479
00:39:13,489 --> 00:39:14,670
It's just weird.

480
00:39:14,650 --> 00:39:24,900
Every day I passed this woman who had a huge goiter, and she sat there absolutely silent, holding a little thing for coins, and her eyes were always glazed with tears.

481
00:39:26,242 --> 00:39:28,603
She just sat there, never looked at me, just sat there.

482
00:39:28,625 --> 00:39:31,847
And as I passed on the other side of the road, I always saw her.

483
00:39:32,288 --> 00:39:35,692
Day after day I passed that poor woman, and I never gave her a penny.

484
00:39:37,273 --> 00:39:39,695
So then I'm coming round the corner,

485
00:39:40,300 --> 00:39:45,289
I'm just wandering around Calcutta, and I come round the corner, and right before me, there's this little girl.

486
00:39:45,989 --> 00:39:48,514
She must be over seven, but she looks round about five.

487
00:39:49,275 --> 00:39:55,186
And she's sucking a dried black banana peel.

488
00:39:55,740 --> 00:40:03,088
And she sees me, and as she sees me, she has the dignity and that destitution to cover her sex.

489
00:40:04,030 --> 00:40:09,076
And that hit me so hard that I just bombed past her.

490
00:40:09,115 --> 00:40:10,757
I never went back to buy her a banana.

491
00:40:11,838 --> 00:40:13,320
It just hit me so hard.

492
00:40:14,221 --> 00:40:17,324
That was my little boy drowned on the beach moment, you know?

493
00:40:17,344 --> 00:40:22,130
Where you suddenly, the awareness of compassion is not enough.

494
00:40:22,150 --> 00:40:23,891
There has to be that contact.

495
00:40:26,655 --> 00:40:30,521
Anyway, that passed.

496
00:40:31,461 --> 00:40:35,005
And that stays with me.

497
00:40:35,065 --> 00:40:42,795
Every time I bring that image to mind, if I feel callous about anything, about, say, refugees and all these sort of people, I just bring that little child to mind.

498
00:40:42,835 --> 00:40:46,179
And that's my connection with all the suffering that's going on these days.

499
00:40:47,079 --> 00:40:49,083
So we're in Calcutta, and we did a couple of naughty things.

500
00:40:49,643 --> 00:40:50,764
And we had opium.

501
00:40:50,885 --> 00:40:51,786
Opium's wonderful.

502
00:40:54,144 --> 00:41:00,052
And I was laid out there all night, and I remember waking up and just watching all these cockroaches going over Dave's body.

503
00:41:01,173 --> 00:41:03,396
I went into the toilet, and there was cockroaches everywhere.

504
00:41:03,416 --> 00:41:04,338
It sounded like a cockroach.

505
00:41:04,358 --> 00:41:05,320
I thought, fantastic.

506
00:41:07,782 --> 00:41:09,945
Anyway, I look, and all my trouble's gone.

507
00:41:10,545 --> 00:41:12,068
Like, you know, what is all this business?

508
00:41:12,128 --> 00:41:12,708
Nothing.

509
00:41:12,768 --> 00:41:13,449
It's stupid.

510
00:41:13,771 --> 00:41:14,210
Get rid of it.

511
00:41:14,492 --> 00:41:16,273
I'm just absolutely blissed out.

512
00:41:16,293 --> 00:41:19,338
Then, of course, it wears off, and I'm depressed and anxious again.

513
00:41:19,358 --> 00:41:21,079
So before long, we're off on a flight.

514
00:41:21,139 --> 00:41:22,481
We're going to Bangkok.

515
00:41:23,085 --> 00:41:27,864
and we do the usual tourist trip and wandering into all these beautiful Buddhist buildings

516
00:41:29,077 --> 00:41:30,398
That's it.

517
00:41:30,418 --> 00:41:32,581
I have no connection at all with Buddhism.

518
00:41:32,601 --> 00:41:33,722
For me, they're just museums.

519
00:41:34,663 --> 00:41:39,869
And again, a bit of naughty stuff and cocaine and all that in Bangkok.

520
00:41:39,889 --> 00:41:41,530
And none of it really held.

521
00:41:42,331 --> 00:41:57,327
It was only years later when I read that book, Emotional Intelligence by Goldman, which brought this whole thing about emotional intelligence into consciousness, that he says in it, if you're a depressive, you tend to be drawn to those sorts of drugs.

522
00:41:57,307 --> 00:42:00,713
that lift you out of your depression.

523
00:42:00,733 --> 00:42:02,574
These are not hallucinatory drugs.

524
00:42:03,817 --> 00:42:07,021
And if you are an anxious person, you're drawn to alcohol.

525
00:42:07,641 --> 00:42:08,483
Well, that's me, isn't it?

526
00:42:09,244 --> 00:42:18,217
So we left Bangkok, we went down through Malaysia, and then we had to walk across the bridge to Singapore.

527
00:42:18,237 --> 00:42:22,523
And as we got to the checkpoint, they sent us back to get the haircut.

528
00:42:22,503 --> 00:42:34,617
So we had to cut my hair off, all of it, and then come back, and then we took this boat, which was a real proper lovely little boat, all the way to Port Moresby.

529
00:42:34,637 --> 00:42:37,000
It was on its way to Cairns and down to Australia.

530
00:42:37,619 --> 00:42:38,420
And that was New Guinea.

531
00:42:38,762 --> 00:42:47,851
We flew then from New Guinea to Medang, and I took up my post as a teacher in the Society of the Divine Word Missionary School.

532
00:42:48,371 --> 00:42:48,893
Yes.

533
00:42:49,496 --> 00:42:52,548
I contacted them again and I got this job myself and Dave.

534
00:42:52,710 --> 00:42:55,260
He taught art and I was teaching English.

535
00:42:56,286 --> 00:43:03,273
So that was a great sort of year and teaching those kids, you know, they actually want to learn, you know what I mean?

536
00:43:03,994 --> 00:43:15,043
And, you know, great things like climbing Mount Harbour and going up this boat, which was run by a priest who was really a sort of dislocated cowboy.

537
00:43:15,744 --> 00:43:26,293
He went up and down barking orders in that strident sort of American thing, giving sermons, selling things and shooting crocodiles.

538
00:43:26,273 --> 00:43:28,436
He had his huge rifle.

539
00:43:28,876 --> 00:43:29,398
He goes, shoot.

540
00:43:31,460 --> 00:43:39,913
And it was during that time that, because I was settled, and as soon as I was settled, you're kidding.

541
00:43:40,454 --> 00:43:44,199
Blown me down after the rush, hasn't it?

542
00:43:44,219 --> 00:43:47,364
And because I'm unsettled, I've got years to go yet.

543
00:43:48,846 --> 00:43:49,827
I'm only at the age of 25.

544
00:43:50,068 --> 00:43:53,512
I'm not even 25 yet.

545
00:43:55,331 --> 00:43:55,932
But I get there.

546
00:43:56,112 --> 00:44:04,288
So anyway, I've got this dreadful thing going on, this nothingness.

547
00:44:04,909 --> 00:44:12,682
I go back from teaching, I don't know what it was, I lie on the bed and I'm suddenly suffused with this enormous fear.

548
00:44:12,663 --> 00:44:21,695
And for something, I don't know, I must have got it from somewhere, I turn towards the fear, and I go into it, and next minute, I'm out of my body.

549
00:44:22,235 --> 00:44:28,844
I'm up there looking down, I turn round, I see that tunnel, swirling tunnel, and I'm back into the body.

550
00:44:29,505 --> 00:44:31,728
All fear of death disappeared.

551
00:44:31,748 --> 00:44:34,371
Not the fear of dying, all fear of death disappeared.

552
00:44:34,992 --> 00:44:38,315
And suddenly, out of the blue, I start writing plays.

553
00:44:40,135 --> 00:44:41,356
I start writing plays.

554
00:44:41,376 --> 00:44:43,338
So then, that's all I've got.

555
00:44:43,358 --> 00:44:43,958
I can't rush you.

556
00:44:44,119 --> 00:44:46,262
I can't rush you.

557
00:44:46,282 --> 00:44:47,302
I'll have to stop midfield.

558
00:44:47,963 --> 00:44:50,086
So then I...

559
00:44:53,411 --> 00:45:02,721
I go down to Australia because I'm interested in theatre and I go to a training school really to learn the art of theatre because I know virtually nothing about it.

560
00:45:03,943 --> 00:45:05,143
And that's where I fall in love again.

561
00:45:06,985 --> 00:45:08,148
Hijacked.

562
00:45:08,989 --> 00:45:09,989
So...

563
00:45:11,016 --> 00:45:12,257
We have a lovely relationship.

564
00:45:12,318 --> 00:45:13,059
It's going fine.

565
00:45:13,099 --> 00:45:15,521
And we're involved in theater.

566
00:45:15,840 --> 00:45:17,663
I get one or two plays going.

567
00:45:19,585 --> 00:45:21,766
And suddenly this idea of marriage comes up.

568
00:45:22,807 --> 00:45:26,170
And my brother just got married.

569
00:45:26,630 --> 00:45:27,512
And I was 27.

570
00:45:28,253 --> 00:45:29,092
And that's what you do.

571
00:45:30,474 --> 00:45:33,717
But in my heart of hearts, I wasn't with it at all.

572
00:45:33,838 --> 00:45:35,039
I wasn't with it at all.

573
00:45:35,059 --> 00:45:39,623
But because of the relationship and because of the love and all that, you get married.

574
00:45:40,429 --> 00:45:43,474
And so we went through a civil service.

575
00:45:43,494 --> 00:45:46,400
And there was something in me that just couldn't handle this.

576
00:45:46,639 --> 00:45:49,606
And I was getting, you know, I was sort of overly happy.

577
00:45:50,246 --> 00:46:01,746
And I remember my dear best man, as we got into the taxi, said to me, you know, Pete, that's what it's called, you know, Pete, you've got to take something seriously.

578
00:46:03,632 --> 00:46:14,525
Well, it was a disaster because somebody who had been a friend, a companion, a lover, somebody whom I shared theatre with, suddenly became a burden.

579
00:46:15,347 --> 00:46:17,969
I'd fallen into the patriarchal trap.

580
00:46:18,550 --> 00:46:19,391
She became a burden.

581
00:46:19,911 --> 00:46:24,516
And we went on a honeymoon and I sort of drained it of joy.

582
00:46:24,556 --> 00:46:29,623
And she said to me at one point, you know, if you carry on like this, I'll leave you.

583
00:46:29,873 --> 00:46:34,757
That's not the sort of conversation you have on a honeymoon, is it?

584
00:46:34,777 --> 00:46:38,583
You don't have that sort of...

585
00:46:42,106 --> 00:46:42,947
It's absolutely awful.

586
00:46:43,347 --> 00:46:49,755
We got to London, and my brother offered us lodgings, and hitting London in November from...

587
00:46:50,135 --> 00:46:58,885
It was the beginning of summer in Australia, and the rain and the cold, and then we hit the theatre, and it was just overwhelming.

588
00:46:58,864 --> 00:47:05,552
I mean, Sydney was a small city, you know, a little small city with a major theatre and a couple of little outlets.

589
00:47:05,972 --> 00:47:08,335
You hit London, and it's just impossible.

590
00:47:09,054 --> 00:47:16,543
I sent my plays off, and I would follow them up, and I got one play back, and it had 600 written on it.

591
00:47:17,103 --> 00:47:19,686
I mean, it was just overwhelming.

592
00:47:19,706 --> 00:47:23,028
I was so depressed, and we were so depressed.

593
00:47:23,329 --> 00:47:24,351
I was dragging her down.

594
00:47:24,570 --> 00:47:26,592
I was dragging her down, too.

595
00:47:26,742 --> 00:47:32,876
We were at the SOAS, School of Oriental and Asian Studies.

596
00:47:33,637 --> 00:47:41,054
And while we were there, this Nigerian approached us and he said he was taking a troop out to Nigeria and would we be interested.

597
00:47:41,615 --> 00:47:43,159
Well, we were completely lost.

598
00:47:43,239 --> 00:47:44,682
We just said yes.

599
00:47:44,731 --> 00:47:46,914
And he went and gave us lodgings.

600
00:47:46,934 --> 00:47:48,938
He said, I'm going to get the group together in a house.

601
00:47:49,418 --> 00:47:54,065
So he actually, I left my brother, went to this house, and it was just an empty room with a mattress in it.

602
00:47:54,246 --> 00:47:55,708
We had to put a line up for the clothes.

603
00:47:56,608 --> 00:48:00,434
And I'm standing there for about two, three weeks, and nothing's happening.

604
00:48:00,454 --> 00:48:03,500
And we're saying, Larry, what's, you know, what's, you know, can you show us the play?

605
00:48:03,519 --> 00:48:04,422
Can you show us the play?

606
00:48:05,322 --> 00:48:09,809
And finally he shows us this play, and it could have been written by a 10-year-old.

607
00:48:10,161 --> 00:48:12,103
And it was an inverted racist play.

608
00:48:12,143 --> 00:48:16,750
It was all about this great black chief who was going to teach these stupid white people something.

609
00:48:17,291 --> 00:48:25,559
And myself and Chris, by the way, who was, her mother was Aboriginal and her father was English, we just looked at each other, got to get out of this, got to get out of this.

610
00:48:26,320 --> 00:48:30,565
Very fortunately, I'd lost contact with Dave, my travelling companion.

611
00:48:30,887 --> 00:48:33,369
And as we got onto a tube, he was right there.

612
00:48:33,929 --> 00:48:37,034
I said, Dave, see?

613
00:48:37,594 --> 00:48:37,755
LAUGHTER

614
00:48:37,735 --> 00:48:39,498
Just as a wonderful thing.

615
00:48:39,539 --> 00:48:41,585
He was moving out of a flat in Highgate.

616
00:48:41,605 --> 00:48:42,907
We were down in Kentish Town.

617
00:48:43,590 --> 00:48:44,853
And it just worked for us.

618
00:48:44,913 --> 00:48:51,489
So the night before, we'd planned the escape because there must have been something in us that told us something like this would happen.

619
00:48:51,811 --> 00:48:54,697
We told him that we weren't going to come.

620
00:48:55,588 --> 00:48:58,956
That evening he came round and he went ballistic.

621
00:48:59,177 --> 00:49:01,362
I mean, it was racist.

622
00:49:01,563 --> 00:49:02,284
It was awful.

623
00:49:02,885 --> 00:49:06,094
And my wife stepped forward and slapped his face.

624
00:49:06,876 --> 00:49:07,697
He made for her.

625
00:49:08,139 --> 00:49:09,201
I grabbed hold of him.

626
00:49:09,681 --> 00:49:10,784
I'm on the floor with him.

627
00:49:10,925 --> 00:49:11,907
I'm holding him down.

628
00:49:12,047 --> 00:49:14,273
I'm shouting, relax, Harry, let go.

629
00:49:15,568 --> 00:49:22,077
I go, finally when he gives up, when he gives up the struggle, we both get up and he's standing there and he goes off again.

630
00:49:22,137 --> 00:49:26,262
I said, yeah, you know, and I'm very penitent and I'm saying this, get back.

631
00:49:27,304 --> 00:49:28,184
And finally he left.

632
00:49:28,224 --> 00:49:34,313
That night, we slept with doors up against the, with chairs up against the doors and a carving knife.

633
00:49:34,994 --> 00:49:36,056
I slept with a carving knife.

634
00:49:36,195 --> 00:49:38,518
It's the case, it's everyday.

635
00:49:38,958 --> 00:49:41,862
Seven o'clock in the morning, we're in that taxi and off we went.

636
00:49:44,458 --> 00:49:45,559
Anyway, it just got worse.

637
00:49:45,661 --> 00:49:46,942
It just got worse and worse and worse.

638
00:49:47,362 --> 00:49:54,672
And eventually, my wife got a job in a theatre company up in Birmingham.

639
00:49:54,692 --> 00:49:56,735
And really, that was the first leaving.

640
00:49:56,954 --> 00:49:58,856
We both knew something was wrong.

641
00:49:59,036 --> 00:50:00,039
We knew it wasn't working.

642
00:50:00,619 --> 00:50:05,826
And her leaving really was the beginning of that, of her leaving me.

643
00:50:05,806 --> 00:50:08,172
I went back home really depressed.

644
00:50:08,231 --> 00:50:10,536
I was back in teaching FE.

645
00:50:10,577 --> 00:50:11,599
It was awful.

646
00:50:12,201 --> 00:50:15,007
I was getting nowhere with my plays.

647
00:50:16,010 --> 00:50:20,822
There was a fantastic opportunity when the director of Earl's Court Theatre actually asked me to come along.

648
00:50:20,842 --> 00:50:22,244
I had an interview with him.

649
00:50:22,224 --> 00:50:23,827
And we were discussing this play I'd read.

650
00:50:23,867 --> 00:50:26,032
I mean, you don't do that with a top director.

651
00:50:26,653 --> 00:50:30,663
And I didn't have the energy to go back with another play.

652
00:50:30,862 --> 00:50:32,266
I didn't keep the contact.

653
00:50:32,425 --> 00:50:33,208
I mean, that's what you do.

654
00:50:33,288 --> 00:50:34,990
Once you've got your foot in, you keep pushing.

655
00:50:35,773 --> 00:50:38,297
And so I'm getting slowly, slowly depressed, like a play.

656
00:50:38,778 --> 00:50:42,005
And that's when Chris tells me that she's fallen in love with somebody else.

657
00:50:44,246 --> 00:50:51,420
So apart from the ego thump, the affection had sort of almost disappeared, really.

658
00:50:51,541 --> 00:50:55,949
So there wasn't that sense of loss that you might get from somebody whom you truly love.

659
00:50:55,969 --> 00:50:59,235
But it put a cap on my situation.

660
00:50:59,737 --> 00:51:05,503
I mean, I was getting nowhere, plays were no good, I was teaching, which I hated doing, I was going nowhere.

661
00:51:05,844 --> 00:51:08,487
So I was in a state of absolute despair.

662
00:51:09,327 --> 00:51:11,489
And I was in a state of shock and despair.

663
00:51:11,710 --> 00:51:17,956
I thought, well, you know, everything I've built up these last years has been absolutely, it's just collapsed.

664
00:51:18,777 --> 00:51:23,362
And then it came to me that it was the most rational thing to do, the most obvious thing to do.

665
00:51:23,402 --> 00:51:24,822
In fact, it was common sense.

666
00:51:24,842 --> 00:51:26,724
I had to go to Japan to meditate.

667
00:51:28,409 --> 00:51:30,472
I don't know how that came.

668
00:51:30,512 --> 00:51:42,929
I'd read a book on Zen Buddhism in Sydney, and I'd walked from where I lived to the shops, looking at myself, observing myself.

669
00:51:42,949 --> 00:51:45,313
By the time I got to the shops, I thought, no, this is going to drive me crazy.

670
00:51:46,034 --> 00:51:46,815
So that was it.

671
00:51:46,855 --> 00:51:47,536
That's my Zen.

672
00:51:47,996 --> 00:51:48,978
That was all I knew.

673
00:51:49,759 --> 00:51:51,742
So I wrote to the Buddhist Society.

674
00:51:52,242 --> 00:51:54,365
How do we find places before Google?

675
00:51:56,422 --> 00:51:58,724
It's a mystery, isn't it?

676
00:51:58,744 --> 00:52:04,548
Anyway, I wrote to them, and they wrote back and gave me 21 reasons as to why I shouldn't go to Japan.

677
00:52:04,568 --> 00:52:10,414
But they put me in touch with Throstle Hole Abbey that had only recently opened up in Hexham in Northumberland.

678
00:52:10,434 --> 00:52:18,961
And from them, they put me in touch with Vajra Bailey, who was teaching in Birmingham, just a bus ride away from where I was living.

679
00:52:18,981 --> 00:52:25,887
So I remember going there on a cold February day, and she was very zen, you know.

680
00:52:26,594 --> 00:52:27,755
And the house was cold.

681
00:52:28,237 --> 00:52:30,802
And we got up to the room, and there was a couple of Greek people there.

682
00:52:31,101 --> 00:52:32,525
And then she took us into the shrine room.

683
00:52:32,545 --> 00:52:34,228
We all bowed, and I thought, this is ridiculous.

684
00:52:34,688 --> 00:52:40,500
And then she sat me on a stool, and she pushed my back in and sat me upright.

685
00:52:40,920 --> 00:52:42,903
And then she said, just watch.

686
00:52:42,923 --> 00:52:44,827
Keep your eyes open like that.

687
00:52:45,168 --> 00:52:48,213
And the instruction was, watch what comes up.

688
00:52:48,193 --> 00:52:53,623
So I sat there for 40 minutes in absolute agony, both emotionally and physically.

689
00:52:54,123 --> 00:52:57,849
But by the end of it, I was just convinced this was going to get me out of this hole.

690
00:52:59,032 --> 00:53:04,161
And she had a room in the house which wasn't occupied, so I went to lodge with her.

691
00:53:04,731 --> 00:53:06,373
So that was February.

692
00:53:07,014 --> 00:53:15,643
By June, by July, I had a job, which was a really easy one, teaching English to foreigners, foreign students.

693
00:53:16,264 --> 00:53:17,746
And I bought a house.

694
00:53:18,867 --> 00:53:21,048
And everything sort of began to move in that way.

695
00:53:21,349 --> 00:53:24,793
That was my last catastrophe, my last big catastrophe.

696
00:53:25,072 --> 00:53:27,456
I've had catastrophes since, but they're only small Cs.

697
00:53:29,077 --> 00:53:31,480
And so I carry on doing that.

698
00:53:32,099 --> 00:53:33,641
I've lost the plot now, just a minute.

699
00:53:35,646 --> 00:53:38,751
Where am I?

700
00:53:38,771 --> 00:53:39,231
Oh, yes.

701
00:53:39,992 --> 00:53:46,000
Then I go up to Zen, and being part of a Zen monastery was like being back in St. Richard's.

702
00:53:46,019 --> 00:53:48,342
It just came to me just with such ease.

703
00:53:48,784 --> 00:53:51,166
I loved going up there, even during the summer holidays.

704
00:53:51,347 --> 00:53:54,271
I'd spend six weeks up at the Throstle Abbey.

705
00:53:55,873 --> 00:54:03,762
And then one day I came back, and I lay on the bed, and this whole, this tremendous...

706
00:54:03,742 --> 00:54:08,530
A fear just filled the whole of my body, every cell, I felt it everywhere.

707
00:54:08,550 --> 00:54:18,666
And there came this picture of this little boy, two years old, going into the front room, shaking my grandfather and saying, he's dead, they've killed him, now they're going to kill me.

708
00:54:20,469 --> 00:54:21,672
Two year old.

709
00:54:21,692 --> 00:54:25,396
So I said to my father, I said, I found grandfather dead in the front room.

710
00:54:25,418 --> 00:54:27,000
He said, no, he died in bed, I was with him.

711
00:54:27,739 --> 00:54:30,793
This tells a lot about trauma, children's trauma.

712
00:54:31,577 --> 00:54:34,289
Obviously my parents weren't getting on, they didn't.

713
00:54:35,384 --> 00:54:49,838
Well, anyway, and I'm thinking I'm the problem they go in and they presume they've killed the old my dear old grandfather And I presume they're gonna kill me now what happened when that trauma came up So you have to be very careful with childhood memories, right?

714
00:54:49,920 --> 00:54:59,670
Because you don't know what you're laying on them actually in the memory I speak to myself in English, but I don't think I had an English in fact Dad I could speak at the age of two But that was the thought

715
00:55:00,612 --> 00:55:12,273
And what happened then was I got a series of images coming through my life to tell me how this trauma had cancered every one of my relationships.

716
00:55:12,293 --> 00:55:13,675
There's your karmic line.

717
00:55:13,735 --> 00:55:16,460
It was just so plain in the face, it was unbelievable.

718
00:55:17,605 --> 00:55:30,302
And then shortly after that, a little bit longer after that, I mean that was such a wonderful relief, and then shortly after that, I'm walking along the road, and on the other side there's a copse of wood.

719
00:55:30,884 --> 00:55:35,030
And as I turn into the copse of wood, I get this thump on the head.

720
00:55:35,590 --> 00:55:46,025
This energy comes down into the heart, it shoots out towards this tree, and what I'm looking at is a kaleidoscopic vortex of energy reaching up into the sky.

721
00:55:46,005 --> 00:55:48,909
Can you imagine that?

722
00:55:48,929 --> 00:55:49,489
Can you imagine that?

723
00:55:51,052 --> 00:55:51,592
Right?

724
00:55:51,612 --> 00:56:11,777
So if you can imagine it, I've just turned towards a copse of wood, there's this gentle thump on my head, energy comes down in the centre of my body, it bursts out of my heart centre, and what I'm looking at is one tree amongst them all, which is this multicoloured, kaleidoscopic vortex of energy reaching up into the sky.

725
00:56:12,398 --> 00:56:18,309
So for a while I was blissed out and I remember particularly looking at this crimson geometry of a rose.

726
00:56:19,731 --> 00:56:24,099
And that lasted for an hour or two and then I got depressed and anxious again.

727
00:56:25,942 --> 00:56:31,693
Now if you were to ask me if I had a choice between those two, you know, what would I have gone for?

728
00:56:32,172 --> 00:56:36,380
This sort of vision or this purification of the heart?

729
00:56:37,492 --> 00:56:38,032
No choice.

730
00:56:38,052 --> 00:56:40,096
You go for the purification of the heart.

731
00:56:40,115 --> 00:56:42,179
Because that's something you can do.

732
00:56:42,639 --> 00:56:44,541
You can't make these other things happen.

733
00:56:45,302 --> 00:56:48,728
And they seem to come to cap a certain level.

734
00:56:48,889 --> 00:56:51,833
They don't come to begin something.

735
00:56:51,913 --> 00:56:53,536
They seem to end a process.

736
00:56:54,195 --> 00:56:58,742
So I don't think that would have been possible, that sort of insight or vision or whatever it was.

737
00:56:59,164 --> 00:57:01,226
It would have been possible without the clearing of the heart.

738
00:57:01,646 --> 00:57:05,472
Now if you look at the Dhammapada, the Buddha puts the practice as

739
00:57:05,452 --> 00:57:09,159
Stop doing evil, do good, purify the heart.

740
00:57:09,980 --> 00:57:11,543
This is the teaching of all the Buddhas.

741
00:57:12,244 --> 00:57:13,485
It's as simple as that.

742
00:57:13,505 --> 00:57:23,101
So this purifying of the heart, what we go through when we're sitting there with all these guns coming up, that is something that we can actually do something directly about.

743
00:57:24,543 --> 00:57:28,070
Now when it comes to this other thing, this bump on the head, what do you think, God?

744
00:57:30,012 --> 00:57:30,954
Big being?

745
00:57:32,182 --> 00:57:42,597
Or just neurons firing through your head, just atomic, subatomic activity, which is firing through the head.

746
00:57:42,619 --> 00:57:44,826
The thing is, I don't know.

747
00:57:45,076 --> 00:57:47,221
It didn't feel like a personal God.

748
00:57:47,260 --> 00:57:51,971
It just felt as though I was given this gift and I've remained at that level.

749
00:57:52,431 --> 00:57:59,688
So if something happens like that to you, you don't have to expand it into some sort of huge cosmology.

750
00:58:00,068 --> 00:58:01,733
It's just something that you receive.

751
00:58:01,813 --> 00:58:03,556
It's just an interesting thing.

752
00:58:03,536 --> 00:58:10,284
And what I understood by that was that the whole of this phenomenal world is nothing but light.

753
00:58:10,764 --> 00:58:11,684
It's nothing but energy.

754
00:58:12,164 --> 00:58:14,668
And that matter is just the coagulation of it.

755
00:58:14,688 --> 00:58:15,307
That's all it is.

756
00:58:15,347 --> 00:58:17,751
That's what it's made of.

757
00:58:18,311 --> 00:58:19,693
There's nothing real.

758
00:58:19,733 --> 00:58:21,153
There's nothing substantial in it.

759
00:58:22,574 --> 00:58:26,980
Anyway, all that passed, and I carried on teaching.

760
00:58:28,320 --> 00:58:30,523
And what were we doing?

761
00:58:31,583 --> 00:59:00,088
is almost time three minutes oh heaven say i'm only at the age of 30. i've only got oh god i'll have to give up i don't think it'd take this long actually i i obviously like doing it well uh there's uh well there's a lot more really but i know i know i know anyway what uh let me just let me just see whether what i can i can quickly

762
00:59:02,228 --> 00:59:04,599
You can carry on and we can keep the donation.

763
00:59:05,362 --> 00:59:07,251
We can keep the... Donation.

764
00:59:09,340 --> 00:59:09,521
Donation.

765
00:59:15,103 --> 00:59:24,699
Well, the story then is basically how I became a Buddhist.

766
00:59:24,818 --> 00:59:26,981
I went up to Throsel, I joined the Zen monastery.

767
00:59:27,483 --> 00:59:33,972
And then through that, through Vajral Bailey, I met the Theravada monk and I did a retreat with him.

768
00:59:33,952 --> 00:59:35,896
And in that retreat I was drawn.

769
00:59:35,956 --> 00:59:46,309
Then the next year the Mahasis came and that gave me a real technique in which to really delve into myself in a way that Zen hadn't really done.

770
00:59:47,050 --> 00:59:53,277
And it was from that that I decided to take a sabbatical from work and I went to Burma with my teacher for six months.

771
00:59:54,237 --> 01:00:11,081
And when I came back, I was really, during that time, this whole business of impermanence became even more clearer because there I actually clearly saw that although this might be, what I'd seen about this tree might be true out there, what's actually true in here

772
01:00:11,061 --> 01:00:15,405
is the arising and passing away, minutely, of consciousnesses.

773
01:00:15,425 --> 01:00:21,833
And that's actually what we're experiencing all the time, just this screen which is flashing, flashing inside us.

774
01:00:22,293 --> 01:00:24,474
And what is it that's aware of it?

775
01:00:24,514 --> 01:00:27,297
What is it that is looking at it?

776
01:00:27,657 --> 01:00:31,442
And that, of course, is our satipanya, that's our intuitive awareness.

777
01:00:31,461 --> 01:00:39,329
And it's that separation which is the process of liberating ourselves from the delusion of thinking that we are this psychophysical organism.

778
01:00:39,630 --> 01:00:42,418
So when I got back, I was really fired up.

779
01:00:42,478 --> 01:00:43,802
I was going to make a go of it.

780
01:00:44,063 --> 01:00:48,717
I got back to college, to the college I was teaching at, and they gave me a promotion for MSA.

781
01:00:49,257 --> 01:00:49,880
Can you believe that?

782
01:00:50,221 --> 01:00:51,284
So I thought, this is what I've got to do.

783
01:00:51,304 --> 01:00:52,608
I'll take it as a bad girl every so often.

784
01:00:52,628 --> 01:00:53,690
I'll come back and get a promotion.

785
01:00:55,206 --> 01:00:56,489
They gave me a promotion.

786
01:00:56,509 --> 01:01:03,458
And then during that time, I was ready really to move into the whole thing of marriage.

787
01:01:03,539 --> 01:01:04,581
I bought a new house.

788
01:01:04,641 --> 01:01:06,182
It was a semi-detached house.

789
01:01:07,043 --> 01:01:10,610
And during that time, I began to fall in love again.

790
01:01:10,650 --> 01:01:12,231
Oh, my goodness.

791
01:01:12,371 --> 01:01:16,878
And so there was then this sort of real potential, you see.

792
01:01:17,260 --> 01:01:25,010
But something else started to creep in, which was, why don't I spend three years as a monk?

793
01:01:24,990 --> 01:01:30,077
Now, the monastic order was established by the Buddha exactly for that reason.

794
01:01:30,818 --> 01:01:36,567
When you look at the rules of the monastic order, you end up simply learning the Dharma or meditating.

795
01:01:36,726 --> 01:01:40,851
There's nothing beyond that if you're keeping the rule as he would want it.

796
01:01:41,193 --> 01:01:51,065
And the whole infrastructure that comes with it in a society is that it holds you there, it holds you in that place.

797
01:01:51,045 --> 01:01:58,380
So I struggled with that for about a year, making lists for and against, and for and against.

798
01:01:58,519 --> 01:02:04,773
And finally, when it really got on top of me, I went to see Ray with the Dam with my teacher, and I said, Banty, I want to become a monk.

799
01:02:04,833 --> 01:02:07,097
And he said, you're too old.

800
01:02:07,077 --> 01:02:08,059
What a relief.

801
01:02:08,762 --> 01:02:10,164
Let's get back and live properly.

802
01:02:10,606 --> 01:02:11,268
So that was it.

803
01:02:11,608 --> 01:02:12,391
But it wouldn't leave me.

804
01:02:12,952 --> 01:02:18,106
So come another six months, I'm back to him and I'm saying, listen, I've got to, I really have to ordain.

805
01:02:18,367 --> 01:02:19,670
Even if it's only for three years.

806
01:02:19,731 --> 01:02:21,896
That was my intention, a three-year ordination.

807
01:02:22,822 --> 01:02:26,708
So again, he said, well, no, he said, you know, you're needed here.

808
01:02:27,150 --> 01:02:29,534
I've become now so much part of that Vihara.

809
01:02:29,914 --> 01:02:31,237
And there were only a few of us.

810
01:02:31,797 --> 01:02:33,961
He wasn't the type of person who collected people.

811
01:02:34,442 --> 01:02:36,766
So there's only about three of us who held the whole Vihara up.

812
01:02:37,467 --> 01:02:40,233
So again, I went away, but this time I wasn't so convinced.

813
01:02:40,253 --> 01:02:46,163
I spent two weeks in meditation with a good friend who read Lord of the Rings while I was suffering in the other room.

814
01:02:47,137 --> 01:02:51,762
If you're listening, Peter, you'll remember.

815
01:02:53,505 --> 01:02:54,987
And I came back absolutely determined.

816
01:02:55,027 --> 01:02:56,548
And when I went to see him again, he said, OK.

817
01:02:57,349 --> 01:02:58,530
So I ordained for three years.

818
01:02:58,630 --> 01:02:59,932
And I remember telling my mother.

819
01:02:59,952 --> 01:03:04,117
And she burst into this enormous veil of tears.

820
01:03:04,217 --> 01:03:05,298
And I put my arm around her.

821
01:03:05,318 --> 01:03:07,501
I said, Mum, I said, it's only for three years.

822
01:03:08,041 --> 01:03:10,885
And she stopped.

823
01:03:10,864 --> 01:03:14,110
In Catholicism, if you're a monk, you disappear.

824
01:03:14,331 --> 01:03:18,476
These days they're not so strict, but you disappear into the monastery, you don't see him again.

825
01:03:18,496 --> 01:03:22,284
So there was a lovely feast for that ordination.

826
01:03:22,643 --> 01:03:31,018
And I went off to work with Goenkaji in his monastery, in his center in Igatpuri, India.

827
01:03:31,838 --> 01:03:37,327
And there, something came out of my neck, some snake or other, it was absolutely awful.

828
01:03:37,307 --> 01:03:40,391
And I came back feeling I'd got rid of some big thing.

829
01:03:40,411 --> 01:03:45,358
And who should be there at the Vihara but Upandita, Said Upandita, some of you might know.

830
01:03:45,898 --> 01:03:50,625
He's one of the prime teachers of the Mahasi tradition, who invited me to come and join him in Burma.

831
01:03:51,184 --> 01:04:00,175
So before I did that, I thought, well, why don't I go and live at Amarawati, the big monastery there, and really get to know what it is to live in this community.

832
01:04:00,697 --> 01:04:05,543
So I turned up there, and it was during that year that there was that...

833
01:04:05,523 --> 01:04:09,887
demonstrations in Burma and all the killing and everything that they did.

834
01:04:10,208 --> 01:04:14,733
It was the one before the one that finally made the military pull back.

835
01:04:15,635 --> 01:04:16,777
So I decided not to go.

836
01:04:17,378 --> 01:04:24,365
And then at the turning of the year, I said to the sangha, I said to the monk, listen, I ought to go and tell Saira Bandita why I've not turned up.

837
01:04:24,766 --> 01:04:25,708
So I went to his

838
01:04:26,617 --> 01:04:28,860
retreat in IMS.

839
01:04:30,945 --> 01:04:32,547
That's Barry, Massachusetts place.

840
01:04:33,148 --> 01:04:36,976
And as soon as I walked into the meditation hall, I just knew this was it.

841
01:04:37,056 --> 01:04:43,809
I didn't want to live in that sort of forest community type of monasticism.

842
01:04:43,829 --> 01:04:47,697
I wanted this hard grind

843
01:04:47,677 --> 01:04:52,248
full on, full metal jacket meditation.

844
01:04:52,750 --> 01:04:54,534
So I decided to go to Burma.

845
01:04:54,934 --> 01:04:55,677
But I couldn't get in.

846
01:04:55,817 --> 01:04:56,739
I got to Bangkok.

847
01:04:56,760 --> 01:04:57,762
I couldn't get a visa.

848
01:04:57,842 --> 01:04:59,606
I ended up in a monastery in the north.

849
01:05:00,068 --> 01:05:03,998
I finally caught up with Upandita down in Penang.

850
01:05:03,978 --> 01:05:06,240
And I did a retreat with him in Penang there.

851
01:05:06,802 --> 01:05:08,844
And by this time, I'm despairing again.

852
01:05:08,925 --> 01:05:10,186
Because it's four years.

853
01:05:10,527 --> 01:05:11,467
I'm not getting anywhere.

854
01:05:11,568 --> 01:05:12,670
I'd determined three years.

855
01:05:12,750 --> 01:05:15,393
I thought, well, I'll give it another what.

856
01:05:15,413 --> 01:05:18,757
So I'm kneeling in front of the Buddha statue.

857
01:05:18,777 --> 01:05:20,719
And I'm saying, look, I've done what I can.

858
01:05:20,800 --> 01:05:24,264
I said, if nothing happens in another year, I'm going to go back and do something useful.

859
01:05:24,902 --> 01:05:32,016
So there was a German monk there whom I was talking to and giving him all my sorrows and telling him where I was and all that.

860
01:05:32,036 --> 01:05:33,978
And he said to me, why don't you go to Sri Lanka?

861
01:05:34,681 --> 01:05:36,103
I said, Sri Lanka?

862
01:05:36,123 --> 01:05:37,065
I never even thought the miles.

863
01:05:37,085 --> 01:05:37,706
He was out there.

864
01:05:38,266 --> 01:05:40,972
So I wrote to Venerable Pali, who was the abbot.

865
01:05:40,992 --> 01:05:42,054
And he wrote back and said, come.

866
01:05:42,715 --> 01:05:43,637
When I got there,

867
01:05:44,494 --> 01:05:46,918
I told him what I wanted to, I said, I just want to sit.

868
01:05:46,938 --> 01:05:48,780
I just want to find somewhere I can sit.

869
01:05:48,800 --> 01:05:57,048
So he gave me a bunch of, he gave me this keys and he, and he, and he directs me to this kuti, this hut at the back of the, of the meditation room, of the, of the monastery.

870
01:05:57,309 --> 01:06:04,315
And when I got there, there's this beautiful little 10 foot by six foot hut with a little chankama, a walking area with walls.

871
01:06:04,436 --> 01:06:04,697
Yeah.

872
01:06:04,737 --> 01:06:05,818
Keep the snakes out and all that.

873
01:06:06,639 --> 01:06:09,422
And a garden all to myself.

874
01:06:09,402 --> 01:06:11,666
And I walked in there and I thought, this is absolutely marvellous.

875
01:06:11,686 --> 01:06:13,349
So I had a toilet built, that was important.

876
01:06:13,909 --> 01:06:27,414
And then there came that day, which was, it's very rare, even in a sense, even in the monastic life, where you didn't have to go into a retreat with the idea that you're going to finish in a month, three months, four months.

877
01:06:27,434 --> 01:06:31,242
I went in with no ending date.

878
01:06:31,222 --> 01:06:40,152
And so I sat there going through all this purification of the heart, doing the meditation, 2 o'clock till 10 o'clock at night, really going for it.

879
01:06:40,172 --> 01:06:42,655
I was absolutely empowered for doing it.

880
01:06:43,177 --> 01:06:47,483
And it was during that time my second trauma appeared out of the blue.

881
01:06:47,882 --> 01:06:54,030
I had this dream of looking across a pond and there was a ghost waving at me.

882
01:06:54,130 --> 01:06:58,916
Now this ghost was exactly what you expect a ghost, a big sheep with two eyes.

883
01:06:58,896 --> 01:07:02,302
And it was on the other side of the park.

884
01:07:02,322 --> 01:07:04,304
And I was absolutely terrified.

885
01:07:05,085 --> 01:07:07,489
And I asked a Jungian psychologist about this.

886
01:07:07,909 --> 01:07:09,030
He said it was a birth trauma.

887
01:07:09,210 --> 01:07:10,793
I don't know.

888
01:07:10,813 --> 01:07:14,778
And then one night, the dream came once, it came twice, this nightmare.

889
01:07:15,099 --> 01:07:18,945
And then one night I woke up and there it was in the corner of the room.

890
01:07:19,826 --> 01:07:27,036
And I remember bouncing on the bed in absolute terror and my little voice saying, what do you want?

891
01:07:27,056 --> 01:07:27,215
LAUGHTER

892
01:07:28,175 --> 01:07:29,659
What do you want?

893
01:07:29,679 --> 01:07:31,041
And the thing just disappeared.

894
01:07:31,061 --> 01:07:32,123
It just fizzled out.

895
01:07:33,126 --> 01:07:34,208
And that was it.

896
01:07:34,349 --> 01:07:36,835
Something just came out of the heart, this trauma.

897
01:07:36,976 --> 01:07:38,800
I still don't know what it means.

898
01:07:39,521 --> 01:07:45,677
And then after that, the clarity of impermanence became even more obvious to me.

899
01:07:45,960 --> 01:07:48,385
And it was so fortunate.

900
01:07:48,425 --> 01:07:53,916
Death doesn't particularly regard you.

901
01:07:53,976 --> 01:07:55,699
Death happens when it wants to do it.

902
01:07:55,719 --> 01:07:57,322
It's usually most inconvenient.

903
01:07:57,884 --> 01:08:02,333
So at that point, just when everything was finished, my father died.

904
01:08:02,313 --> 01:08:06,858
So I remember receiving the news and I was walking back towards the Kooten.

905
01:08:06,918 --> 01:08:07,659
I'm crying.

906
01:08:08,199 --> 01:08:11,802
But I didn't cry long because when I reflected on his life, you know, he had a good life.

907
01:08:11,822 --> 01:08:12,603
He was a happy man.

908
01:08:12,623 --> 01:08:15,427
He was very sanguine, et cetera, et cetera, you know.

909
01:08:15,867 --> 01:08:16,648
And I loved him much.

910
01:08:17,248 --> 01:08:19,952
And I went back for his funeral.

911
01:08:21,052 --> 01:08:25,917
And then I thought, well, somebody has to stay with my mother, comfort my mother.

912
01:08:25,938 --> 01:08:30,582
So I stayed with my mother for a year and I was a real Job's comforter.

913
01:08:31,162 --> 01:08:31,863
You know what I mean?

914
01:08:32,992 --> 01:08:38,445
I think I called her more misery.

915
01:08:38,527 --> 01:08:40,452
Death stirs things up, you know?

916
01:08:40,612 --> 01:08:41,514
Death stirs things up.

917
01:08:41,533 --> 01:08:46,226
I mean, if there's one woman I love to bitch, it's my mother, you know?

918
01:08:46,247 --> 01:08:47,489
And I could strangle her.

919
01:08:50,271 --> 01:09:01,268
So I stayed with her for one year and then I came back and I said to the family, I don't think she's going to live long because she doesn't have the moral support.

920
01:09:01,287 --> 01:09:06,454
Anyway, what happened was I went back with the fierce intention again to start and off I went.

921
01:09:07,036 --> 01:09:12,042
And come about, it wasn't very long, something like that, she went seriously ill.

922
01:09:13,221 --> 01:09:18,913
And so I came back, and I felt really bad about that year of comforting.

923
01:09:18,934 --> 01:09:21,259
And so I really made an effort this time.

924
01:09:21,279 --> 01:09:24,125
And you couldn't live with my mother.

925
01:09:24,164 --> 01:09:25,346
It was impossible.

926
01:09:25,887 --> 01:09:28,153
So we got her into a lovely nursing home.

927
01:09:28,493 --> 01:09:29,615
And at first, she hated it.

928
01:09:29,836 --> 01:09:32,721
She talked about le carrozze, these wheelchairs.

929
01:09:32,742 --> 01:09:34,064
She couldn't stand the wheelchairs.

930
01:09:34,045 --> 01:09:36,948
But when I went to see her after about a month, she was perfectly at home.

931
01:09:37,449 --> 01:09:38,591
She was back in boarding school.

932
01:09:38,871 --> 01:09:40,594
She was with all these friends, all these women.

933
01:09:40,613 --> 01:09:41,595
She was chatting away.

934
01:09:41,635 --> 01:09:42,837
She was the life of the party.

935
01:09:42,856 --> 01:09:44,259
It was absolutely wonderful to see her.

936
01:09:45,060 --> 01:09:52,009
Anyway, again, most convenient, she decided to have a stroke just before I was off to Sri Lanka.

937
01:09:52,750 --> 01:09:54,612
And she died within three days.

938
01:09:56,033 --> 01:10:02,802
So having buried her, I then went back to Sri Lanka and started the process again.

939
01:10:03,712 --> 01:10:07,458
So the death of my mother was really weird.

940
01:10:08,119 --> 01:10:09,082
I felt like an orphan.

941
01:10:09,582 --> 01:10:11,546
I mean, I was, what, 45 years old?

942
01:10:11,966 --> 01:10:15,814
And I felt as though, yeah, I felt like an orphan.

943
01:10:15,875 --> 01:10:21,746
I wrote this big, long letter to one of my cousins in Italy explaining how awful I felt.

944
01:10:21,765 --> 01:10:22,847
I don't know what he's done with it.

945
01:10:23,268 --> 01:10:24,149
So...

946
01:10:24,417 --> 01:10:25,798
And that passed.

947
01:10:26,198 --> 01:10:30,122
And then I went back and really went for it again.

948
01:10:30,143 --> 01:10:33,426
And there came this point where, oh, it was just impossible.

949
01:10:34,747 --> 01:10:38,832
The restlessness, the pain that was coming out of me, it was just constant.

950
01:10:38,853 --> 01:10:39,594
It was day in.

951
01:10:39,613 --> 01:10:40,854
I woke up into it.

952
01:10:41,155 --> 01:10:42,356
I carried it through the day.

953
01:10:42,737 --> 01:10:43,859
I slept into it.

954
01:10:44,259 --> 01:10:46,521
I woke up and it just went on day after day.

955
01:10:46,801 --> 01:10:50,525
And it got to a point when I thought, no, I just can't go on.

956
01:10:51,451 --> 01:10:54,418
I can't go on, I'm going to stop.

957
01:10:54,439 --> 01:10:55,863
Well, I can't tell you what happened then.

958
01:10:56,364 --> 01:11:06,472
When I gave up at that moment, there came into me this enormous terror, which picked me up and threw me back onto the meditation cushion.

959
01:11:06,453 --> 01:11:07,895
Because that's the last thing you do.

960
01:11:08,416 --> 01:11:13,824
You can stop for a while, you can leave it, you can get drunk, you can do anything, but you never give up.

961
01:11:14,286 --> 01:11:16,850
Once you're on the path, you move on the path.

962
01:11:16,869 --> 01:11:18,552
If you give up, there's only one way to go.

963
01:11:19,154 --> 01:11:20,135
You're going to go down.

964
01:11:20,775 --> 01:11:22,578
And I was horrified.

965
01:11:23,039 --> 01:11:31,092
I can't tell you the horror that struck me when I realized that I'd actually given up on my spiritual journey.

966
01:11:31,073 --> 01:11:32,743
So I got over that pretty quickly.

967
01:11:33,126 --> 01:11:36,948
I just sat on the cushion and mowed my way through it.

968
01:11:37,266 --> 01:11:41,192
So then I'm getting, my body is beginning to suffer, I think.

969
01:11:41,372 --> 01:11:43,475
I don't know, I'm beginning to feel weak.

970
01:11:43,756 --> 01:11:44,697
I'm not strong.

971
01:11:45,136 --> 01:11:49,182
I write to a monk I know in London, who's Dr. Vajrayana.

972
01:11:49,203 --> 01:11:53,028
And I write with the intention of staying there just to get my body right.

973
01:11:53,047 --> 01:11:58,814
So I turn up at the London Buddhist Vihara, and I've got this back room, and I'm basically meditating.

974
01:11:59,515 --> 01:12:03,881
And the monk who was teaching there decided to leave the order and get married.

975
01:12:04,654 --> 01:12:06,278
So who did they ask to sit on the podium?

976
01:12:06,698 --> 01:12:06,998
It's me.

977
01:12:07,458 --> 01:12:17,975
So I'm sitting there, and I'm slowly becoming to understand that whatever took me to Sri Lanka, that energy, that inspiration was dying away.

978
01:12:18,537 --> 01:12:20,019
I didn't want to go back there.

979
01:12:20,038 --> 01:12:21,502
How would I live in Britain?

980
01:12:21,942 --> 01:12:26,729
So the only way you can live in Britain, if you want to find somewhere...

981
01:12:26,710 --> 01:12:29,774
spiritually supportive, was to begin to teach.

982
01:12:29,793 --> 01:12:30,654
I needed support.

983
01:12:31,737 --> 01:12:33,259
So that's where the teaching began.

984
01:12:33,679 --> 01:12:36,182
But, of course, I had this horror of teaching.

985
01:12:36,403 --> 01:12:38,386
I really didn't want to do it.

986
01:12:39,127 --> 01:12:52,465
So I'm teaching weekend retreats, and come the year 2000, I decide, look, I've got to sort this out, and I go on a retreat with Upandita, outside Upandita's place, Panditarama, in the middle of Rangoon.

987
01:12:52,444 --> 01:12:55,788
And when you go on retreat with a problem, you don't think about the problem.

988
01:12:55,828 --> 01:12:56,730
You just go on retreat.

989
01:12:57,532 --> 01:13:01,015
And whatever is causing the problem will, in fact, just sort itself out.

990
01:13:01,235 --> 01:13:03,640
In other words, what's causing the problem is confusion.

991
01:13:04,239 --> 01:13:05,402
That's what's normally the problem.

992
01:13:05,721 --> 01:13:13,332
And if you just sit with it, if you just stay with it, as confusion, as fear of making a decision, eventually it just sorts itself out.

993
01:13:13,351 --> 01:13:16,055
So that was another rotten retreat.

994
01:13:16,235 --> 01:13:17,237
Six weeks of misery.

995
01:13:17,658 --> 01:13:22,384
And then when it passed, it was lovely and peaceful for a week.

996
01:13:23,393 --> 01:13:28,780
So I'm down at the end of the retreat and I'm in the hall there and I'm looking at the bookcase and my eye falls on this book.

997
01:13:29,402 --> 01:13:34,628
And it's all the stuff on teaching that's taken out of A Course of Miracles.

998
01:13:35,029 --> 01:13:37,132
Some of you might know that book, A Course of Miracles.

999
01:13:37,432 --> 01:13:39,055
It's a big book and it's got a teacher's book with it.

1000
01:13:39,716 --> 01:13:47,207
And I pick it out and I'm reading it and by the end of that book I'm absolutely certain that what I've got to do is teach.

1001
01:13:47,186 --> 01:13:47,828
How weird.

1002
01:13:48,912 --> 01:13:49,534
It happens, doesn't it?

1003
01:13:49,916 --> 01:13:53,748
You've got this problem, you know, and you call for help and the answer comes.

1004
01:13:53,828 --> 01:13:54,932
It comes in its own time.

1005
01:13:55,694 --> 01:13:58,664
So I get back to Britain.

1006
01:13:59,421 --> 01:14:02,626
And I go back to the Vihara.

1007
01:14:02,645 --> 01:14:04,006
And I set up a little trust.

1008
01:14:04,347 --> 01:14:07,631
And before we know it, we've collected 25,000 pounds to open a center.

1009
01:14:08,412 --> 01:14:10,255
And that's where the big mistake comes.

1010
01:14:10,595 --> 01:14:13,257
I open up in the north of London.

1011
01:14:13,518 --> 01:14:15,079
All my support is in the south.

1012
01:14:15,881 --> 01:14:18,023
I completely forget that London is not a city.

1013
01:14:18,344 --> 01:14:19,484
It's a collection of villages.

1014
01:14:20,506 --> 01:14:23,949
And you don't go from the south to the north for an evening meeting.

1015
01:14:24,690 --> 01:14:26,273
That's a two-hour journey.

1016
01:14:27,079 --> 01:14:29,444
So on the opening day, 30-odd people came.

1017
01:14:30,306 --> 01:14:33,273
And what happened was they never came again.

1018
01:14:34,114 --> 01:14:36,198
And I had this, they never came again, that's it.

1019
01:14:36,760 --> 01:14:48,243
And come September, Mattesh, a Dutch student, he was a student at one of the London universities.

1020
01:14:48,881 --> 01:14:49,682
doing a PhD.

1021
01:14:50,023 --> 01:14:50,764
And he's very good.

1022
01:14:50,783 --> 01:14:51,905
He supported me all the way.

1023
01:14:51,926 --> 01:14:52,445
He's a lovely man.

1024
01:14:53,067 --> 01:15:00,414
And I said to him, if we don't have somebody by the end of September, we're not going to have a group.

1025
01:15:00,435 --> 01:15:03,779
So we advertised all over the place, made these little stickers.

1026
01:15:03,838 --> 01:15:05,782
And I had two young fellas, and they cycled everywhere.

1027
01:15:05,801 --> 01:15:08,585
And they put these stickers everywhere, laundrettes, libraries, everywhere.

1028
01:15:08,864 --> 01:15:10,367
And they had the wrong telephone number.

1029
01:15:11,122 --> 01:15:13,286
Yeah, you learn, you learn.

1030
01:15:13,766 --> 01:15:17,231
So the first night the neighbor came and he never came again.

1031
01:15:18,292 --> 01:15:20,216
The second night nobody came.

1032
01:15:20,515 --> 01:15:23,319
So by October I'm thinking this is a disaster.

1033
01:15:24,462 --> 01:15:30,069
By the end of that season the Sri Lankans had come to help us, especially Sita.

1034
01:15:30,128 --> 01:15:34,836
She was always there helping me, Dr. Sita Sriwarni.

1035
01:15:34,815 --> 01:15:38,942
And then we had this six-week retreat over winter.

1036
01:15:38,981 --> 01:15:39,884
We closed the place down.

1037
01:15:39,923 --> 01:15:40,645
There were five of us.

1038
01:15:41,065 --> 01:15:42,969
And I decided that it was not going to work.

1039
01:15:43,088 --> 01:15:43,670
I've got to get out.

1040
01:15:44,291 --> 01:15:47,756
Luckily, there was a man who was on retreat with me, Peter, who knew the bachelors.

1041
01:15:48,497 --> 01:15:50,038
And he got in touch with the bachelors.

1042
01:15:50,680 --> 01:15:51,841
That's Stephen and Martine.

1043
01:15:51,881 --> 01:15:54,185
Some of you might have read their books and might know them.

1044
01:15:54,206 --> 01:15:57,671
And he told them that the next cosmic Buddha was in the north of London.

1045
01:15:58,613 --> 01:15:58,932
So there you go.

1046
01:15:58,912 --> 01:16:05,261
So they came up to see me, and it was just one of these lovely

1047
01:16:05,747 --> 01:16:06,829
Oh, my goodness.

1048
01:16:07,229 --> 01:16:08,573
I'm really going over the top now.

1049
01:16:08,693 --> 01:16:09,153
It's 3.15.

1050
01:16:09,514 --> 01:16:10,314
I'm rushing now.

1051
01:16:10,335 --> 01:16:12,118
I'm rushing through, right?

1052
01:16:12,418 --> 01:16:13,279
Where do I need to get to?

1053
01:16:13,720 --> 01:16:15,484
So anyway, this is it.

1054
01:16:15,503 --> 01:16:16,204
This is the last bit.

1055
01:16:16,564 --> 01:16:21,493
So it was just one of those times when Gaia House was stuck.

1056
01:16:21,833 --> 01:16:23,275
The bachelors had moved to France.

1057
01:16:23,817 --> 01:16:27,762
They needed somebody there to look after the personals, about 12 personals.

1058
01:16:28,283 --> 01:16:32,751
So I went to see Christina Fellman, and I thought it was a great place.

1059
01:16:33,405 --> 01:16:40,578
And when I was there, I became really my Dharma teachers, my Dharma teacher centre, college.

1060
01:16:41,399 --> 01:16:48,069
Because not only was I treating with people who had come on personal retreat, some of them were ill with ME and things like that.

1061
01:16:48,329 --> 01:16:56,443
Some were, you know, psychological problems, not mental illnesses, but, you know, passing depressions and lots of stuff.

1062
01:16:56,422 --> 01:17:08,145
I had to deal with some of the managers who were running the place and I was given the chance to run these eight-week retreats in the Mahasi system twice a year.

1063
01:17:09,006 --> 01:17:15,158
And it was during that time that I realised that there was a little space to start something like this.

1064
01:17:15,137 --> 01:17:18,081
So after about a year or two, I decided to leave.

1065
01:17:18,641 --> 01:17:26,011
I was never really fully into the teachers' organisation there because it's a very lay organisation.

1066
01:17:26,131 --> 01:17:32,918
And so, again, I came to a choice as to whether to disrobe and become a lay teacher or to remain a monk.

1067
01:17:32,939 --> 01:17:38,444
It was a bit like, for those of you who know the imagery, a bit like being a Catholic priest amongst Quakers.

1068
01:17:38,998 --> 01:17:40,342
So I gave up.

1069
01:17:40,844 --> 01:17:41,987
I decided to leave.

1070
01:17:42,047 --> 01:17:47,202
And then we just went through the whole business of a trust.

1071
01:17:47,221 --> 01:17:54,020
I have a special thanks to Anne Ashton, who was the treasurer, who was the...

1072
01:17:54,001 --> 01:18:14,317
Accounts person at Gaia House and she took us through this whole process of a lawyer We've got a lawyer from down in London, you know a simple letter to the to the charitable trust and we had it, you know, and it only cost us two and a half thousand pound and then and then we set it up and Well, then it's just history, isn't it?

1073
01:18:14,337 --> 01:18:17,983
You know, I find this place and from then on I think you know, it's all about

1074
01:18:18,654 --> 01:18:20,157
So let me see now.

1075
01:18:20,176 --> 01:18:20,618
Let me see.

1076
01:18:20,658 --> 01:18:21,279
Let me see.

1077
01:18:21,338 --> 01:18:22,720
I've got to finish now.

1078
01:18:22,740 --> 01:18:23,462
This is the coda.

1079
01:18:24,023 --> 01:18:25,666
This is finally the coda.

1080
01:18:25,706 --> 01:18:27,509
Nobody's really rushed me.

1081
01:18:27,809 --> 01:18:29,311
I could have been here three hours.

1082
01:18:32,115 --> 01:18:35,121
So first, here we go.

1083
01:18:35,140 --> 01:18:35,622
All right.

1084
01:18:35,822 --> 01:18:35,921
Okay.

1085
01:18:36,609 --> 01:18:41,420
So you might ask now, after all this, where am I?

1086
01:18:41,460 --> 01:18:42,682
Everybody wants to know where you are.

1087
01:18:43,283 --> 01:18:48,194
So the Buddha gives this image of an ocean in which beings are swimming underneath, completely lost.

1088
01:18:48,215 --> 01:18:52,384
Others bob their head up and down, and some are stable, and they can see there's an island.

1089
01:18:52,725 --> 01:18:56,592
An island which is both in, but not of, this world.

1090
01:18:57,367 --> 01:19:00,951
Now for me, it wasn't an ocean, it's been a swamp, okay?

1091
01:19:00,970 --> 01:19:05,695
So I'm stuck in this swamp with crocodiles, and every so often there's a bit of a clearing, and that's it.

1092
01:19:06,216 --> 01:19:09,399
And all I can say is that I know where the island is.

1093
01:19:09,761 --> 01:19:10,462
That's the important thing.

1094
01:19:10,502 --> 01:19:11,363
I know where the island is.

1095
01:19:11,603 --> 01:19:13,185
Does that mean I'm making a beeline for it?

1096
01:19:13,324 --> 01:19:14,225
Not at all.

1097
01:19:14,246 --> 01:19:16,507
I slip over here, slip over, I sometimes turn my back on it.

1098
01:19:16,788 --> 01:19:19,712
But generally speaking, I'm on the way, right?

1099
01:19:19,692 --> 01:19:21,173
So that's where you've got to get to.

1100
01:19:21,713 --> 01:19:38,011
So you can see how I just stumbled and bumbled and just blundered my way through life, but not without lots of summery somersaults and sticky toffee pudding with custard.

1101
01:19:38,030 --> 01:19:41,113
And I've landed here in an area of outstanding natural beauty.

1102
01:19:41,154 --> 01:19:44,738
It's not bad, is it?

1103
01:19:46,000 --> 01:19:51,126
Anyway, so now, there are two things.

1104
01:19:51,166 --> 01:19:57,895
I wanted to talk about some of my spiritual experience, because I want to really release people from keeping it to themselves.

1105
01:19:58,314 --> 01:20:04,002
Often, you know, I get meditators come to me and tell me similar things that I've told you, and I've said, have you told anybody?

1106
01:20:04,042 --> 01:20:05,404
They say, no, it's only just for me.

1107
01:20:05,725 --> 01:20:11,332
Because there isn't that framework within which they feel free to express themselves.

1108
01:20:11,351 --> 01:20:15,737
And often, of course, if they can't, they get into what's known as a spiritual emergency.

1109
01:20:15,716 --> 01:20:20,922
where it just sends them offline and they end up with a doctor.

1110
01:20:20,943 --> 01:20:23,667
And if the doctor's not sympathetic, of course, you're back on drugs.

1111
01:20:24,127 --> 01:20:27,551
It's a psychotic interlude or something.

1112
01:20:27,570 --> 01:20:31,416
So be much more open about out-of-body experiences.

1113
01:20:32,056 --> 01:20:36,881
I go to Gaia and occasionally I'll ask a group of 25 how many people have had out-of-body experiences.

1114
01:20:37,162 --> 01:20:37,923
Five hands go up.

1115
01:20:38,524 --> 01:20:41,488
Now, I wouldn't say that's the same percentage for the general population,

1116
01:20:41,467 --> 01:20:45,943
But it's not an unknown experience, you know?

1117
01:20:48,842 --> 01:20:56,190
And so finally, what is it that I would really like to pass on to you?

1118
01:20:56,270 --> 01:20:58,373
What is it I've come to know?

1119
01:20:58,394 --> 01:21:04,381
I've come to realize that the difference between me and the Buddha is one of degree and not of kind.

1120
01:21:04,980 --> 01:21:06,944
And that the difference between me and you is the same.

1121
01:21:07,623 --> 01:21:16,875
And that the difference between us and all sentient beings, all these animals, if you look into their eyes, the mirrors, the windows to the soul, you'll see they have this intelligence.

1122
01:21:16,854 --> 01:21:24,905
And that, because of that, the force that lies in us all is to seek happiness.

1123
01:21:26,047 --> 01:21:31,555
And because we're deluded, we create all this suffering, but at some point there has to be a turning.

1124
01:21:33,418 --> 01:21:41,529
You turn round upon it, and at some point in your life, you're pushed by your own suffering to move towards the end of it.

1125
01:21:41,914 --> 01:21:46,140
Now Kant has this little phrase called a categorical imperative.

1126
01:21:46,460 --> 01:21:52,608
And he's talking about the model law, whereby, if I can just quote him here, if I can just find it just a minute.

1127
01:21:55,931 --> 01:21:57,373
I can find it somewhere.

1128
01:21:57,394 --> 01:21:58,635
I thought I'd written it down.

1129
01:21:59,957 --> 01:22:00,497
Oh, what a shame.

1130
01:22:02,179 --> 01:22:03,501
It's the definition of it, you see.

1131
01:22:09,774 --> 01:22:22,231
A categorical imperative by which he means that if you make a moral law, like for instance not to steal, that is unconditionally and completely applicable to all human beings.

1132
01:22:23,012 --> 01:22:29,162
In the category of stealing, it is an imperative, a command that all human beings obey that.

1133
01:22:29,502 --> 01:22:32,846
You can't say one human being can steal and others can't.

1134
01:22:32,827 --> 01:22:45,692
So I would like to say that it is a categorical imperative that all beings, all sentient beings, will become fully liberated from all suffering forever.

1135
01:22:47,836 --> 01:22:48,556
Absolutely.

1136
01:22:52,266 --> 01:23:11,827
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused confusion and befuddlement, and that you will, by your devotion to the practice, unrelenting, unremitting devotion to the practice, come to the end of suffering forever, sooner rather than later.

1137
01:23:13,268 --> 01:23:18,172
Sadhu, sadhu, sadhu.

1138
01:23:21,037 --> 01:23:24,295
I could have gone on.

1139
01:23:28,476 --> 01:23:33,342
Sorry about that.

